# Leviathan Crypto Changelog

## v3.0.0

### Features

- **AESGCMSIVCipher.** AES-256-GCM-SIV (RFC 8452) is now a first-class
  `CipherSuite` peer to `SerpentCipher` and `XChaCha20Cipher`. Use with
  `Seal`, `SealStream`, `OpenStream`, `SealStreamPool`, and `KyberSuite`.
  `formatEnum: 0x04`, `keySize: 32`, `tagSize: 16`. Nonce-misuse-resistant
  authenticated encryption, single-stream key reuse across the same
  nonce reduces IND-CPA to message-equality leakage rather than full
  break, the strongest nonce-reuse posture among the three shipped symmetric suites.

  HtE explicit-commitment construction matches `XChaCha20Cipher`:
  HKDF-SHA-256 emits 64 bytes from `(masterKey, nonce, INFO || header)`,
  bytes 0..32 are the per-stream AES-GCM-SIV key (no subkey-derivation
  step, AES-GCM-SIV's nonce is 12 bytes, used directly per chunk; there
  is no HChaCha20 analog), bytes 32..64 are a 32-byte commitment in the
  preamble. `OpenStream` and `SealStreamPool` verify the commitment in
  constant time before any chunk is processed; a wrong key fails fast
  with `AuthenticationError` carrying the discriminator
  `commitment-aes-gcm-siv`. This closes the Invisible Salamanders attack
  surface, POLYVAL is not key-committing on its own (same posture as
  Poly1305).

  Header binding into HKDF info: tampering with `formatEnum`, the framed
  flag, the nonce, or `chunkSize` produces different keys, so the AEAD
  fails on the first chunk rather than relying on indirect detection
  through chunk-boundary mismatch.

  The cipher suite is AES-256 only. The standalone `AESGCMSIV` primitive
  class continues to support both AES-128 and AES-256 (RFC 8452 §6).

- **KyberSuite + AES variants.** `KyberSuite(MlKem512/768/1024,
  AESGCMSIVCipher)` produces `formatEnum` 0x14, 0x24, and 0x34 with
  preamble sizes 820/1140/1620 bytes, identical to the XChaCha20 KEM
  variants since both carry the 32-byte commitment after the KEM
  ciphertext. The `KyberSuite` factory required no source changes;
  composition is generic over the inner `CipherSuite`.

- **AESGenerator.** AES-256 ECB counter-mode PRF for `Fortuna`'s
  pluggable `Generator` slot. Restores the original Fortuna spec
  primitive (Practical Cryptography §9.4), previously the library only
  offered `SerpentGenerator` and `ChaCha20Generator`, both of which were
  spec deviations from the original Ferguson-Schneier construction.
  Pair with `SHA256Hash` or `SHA3_256Hash` for the full six-combination
  matrix (`AESGenerator`, `SerpentGenerator`, `ChaCha20Generator` × two
  hashes). `keySize: 32`, `blockSize: 16`, `counterSize: 16`. Requires
  `init({ aes: aesWasm })` plus the chosen hash module.

- **AES pool worker.** `AESGCMSIVCipher.createPoolWorker()` spawns a
  classic worker via blob URL from a bundled IIFE, the same pipeline
  `XChaCha20Cipher` and `SerpentCipher` use. Workers instantiate their
  own `aes` WASM module from a pre-compiled `WebAssembly.Module` and
  hold the derived AES-GCM-SIV key for the pool's lifetime. Import
  graph audited, the AES pool-worker IIFE bundle pulls no
  `chacha20`/`serpent`/`kyber`/`MlKem` identifiers.

- **KAT corpus extended.** Pinned vectors generated by the existing
  `gen-seal-vectors.ts`, `gen-sealstream-vectors.ts`, and
  `gen-fortuna-vectors.ts` scripts now cover AES end-to-end.
  `seal_aes_v3.ts`, `sealstream_aes_v3.ts`, and two new entries in
  `fortuna_kat.ts` (`aes_sha2`, `aes_sha3`). Each vector is
  cross-verified at generation time against the underlying primitives
  (raw AES-GCM-SIV WASM ops; raw AES-256 ECB for the Fortuna generator).

- **ML-DSA.** FIPS 204 Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Standard
  is now a first-class peer to ML-KEM. Three classes, `MlDsa44`,
  `MlDsa65`, `MlDsa87` (NIST security categories 2/3/5), share one
  `mldsa` WASM module with SIMD-required NTT. Pure ML-DSA exposes
  `keygen` / `keygenDerand`, hedged `sign` (FIPS 204 §3.4 recommended
  default), `signDeterministic`, `signDerand` (CAVP / externally-supplied
  rnd), and `verify`. HashML-DSA (FIPS 204 §5.4) exposes `signHash` /
  `signHashDeterministic` / `signHashDerand` / `verifyHash` with all
  twelve approved pre-hash functions from §5.4.1: SHA2-{224, 256, 384,
  512, 512/224, 512/256}, SHA3-{224, 256, 384, 512}, SHAKE128 (32-byte
  output), and SHAKE256 (64-byte output). The pre-hash domain separator
  byte (0x01 vs 0x00 for pure ML-DSA) plus the per-function OID DER
  bytes from NIST CSOR enforce cross-protocol domain separation,
  signatures from `signHash` cannot verify under `verify` on the same
  key, closing the FIPS 204 §3.6.4 attack surface.

  Initialize via `init({ mldsa: ..., sha3: ... })`; `init({ sha2: ... })`
  is additionally required when the chosen pre-hash is in the SHA-2
  family. Subpath exports: `leviathan-crypto/mldsa` and
  `leviathan-crypto/mldsa/embedded`. The ACVP corpus (keyGen / sigGen /
  sigVer / HashML-DSA across all three parameter sets, hedged plus
  deterministic plus derand modes) is byte-identical to the published
  vectors. Constant-time c̃ comparison on verify, deterministic and
  hedged signing paths, and HintBitUnpack's three malformed-input
  checks (FIPS 204 Algorithm 21 lines 4, 9, 17, the SUF-CMA fix from
  §D.3) are exercised by the gate tests in `test/unit/mldsa/`. Every
  WASM region holding a secret or secret-derived intermediate is wiped
  on the way out (success and failure paths).

- **PQC verifier coverage.** The independent Rust verifier
  (`scripts/verify-vectors`) now oracles the ML-DSA ACVP corpora
  (keyGen, sigGen, sigVer, HashML-DSA) against a separate-lineage
  `ml-dsa` crate, alongside the existing ML-KEM coverage. Both PQC
  algorithms now have end-to-end cross-implementation verification on
  every CI run.

- **SP 800-185 cSHAKE and KMAC.** Six new classes built on top of the
  existing `sha3` WASM module: `CSHAKE128`, `CSHAKE256`, `KMAC128`,
  `KMAC256`, `KMACXOF128`, `KMACXOF256`. cSHAKE provides customizable
  SHAKE output with a domain-separation string. KMAC is the Keccak-based
  MAC, with `outLen` bound at construction so the `right_encode(L*8)`
  suffix binds the output length into the MAC computation. KMACXOF
  produces caller-driven output via `squeeze`. The four SP 800-185 §2.3
  encoding helpers (`leftEncode`, `rightEncode`, `encodeString`,
  `bytepad`) live in TypeScript and stream into the existing
  `keccakAbsorb` path; two new AssemblyScript inits (`cshake128Init`,
  `cshake256Init`) set the cSHAKE domain separation byte. The API is
  byte-oriented end to end; no bit-level inputs are exposed. Subpath
  exports: `leviathan-crypto/sha3` and `leviathan-crypto/sha3/embedded`.

  KMAC fixed-output variants ship with a static `verify(tag, key, msg,
  customization)` that recomputes the MAC and constant-time-compares
  via `constantTimeEqual`. On mismatch it throws `AuthenticationError`
  with discriminator `'kmac128'` or `'kmac256'`; on match it returns
  `true`. KMACXOF variants intentionally have no static `verify` because
  the output length is not canonical; squeeze the expected number of
  bytes and use `constantTimeEqual` directly.

  Customization is required at every call site: the cSHAKE classes
  reject empty customization (the construction would collapse to plain
  SHAKE) and point callers to `SHAKE128`/`SHAKE256` if that is what
  they wanted. KMAC rejects empty keys for the same structural reason
  and points to `CSHAKE128`/`CSHAKE256`. The vector corpus pins 24
  records sourced from NIST SP 800-185 sample documents plus the NIST
  ACVP byte-aligned subset; both are checked into
  `test/vectors/kmac.ts` and tracked by `test/vectors/SHA256SUMS`.
  The `scripts/verify-vectors` Rust crate uses `tiny-keccak` as an
  independent oracle, and `test/unit/sha3/kmac.test.ts` runs the WASM
  implementation against the same records. Two `@internal` test-only
  helpers (`_cshake128Raw`, `_cshake256Raw`) exist solely so ACVP
  records carrying NIST-reserved function names exercise the WASM
  sponge end to end; they are not part of the public surface.

- **Ed25519.** RFC 8032 Edwards-Curve Digital Signature
  Algorithm lands as the first classical signature primitive in
  the library. The new `Ed25519` class covers both modes:
  pure Ed25519 (RFC 8032 §5.1.6, signature generation) signs the
  message bytes directly, and Ed25519ph (RFC 8032 §5.1.7,
  signature verification, with the dom2(F=1, ctx) prehash
  binding) signs a caller-supplied SHA-512 digest with an
  optional context up to 255 bytes. Verification is strict per
  FIPS 186-5 §7.6.4: non-canonical pk or R encodings, `s >= L`,
  small-order pk values, and signature-equation mismatches all
  return `false`. The strict gates close the ACVP
  `testPassed=false` sigVer malleation paths.

  The sign path carries a fault-injection defence inherited from
  the dalek discipline: the caller passes pk alongside sk, the
  WASM re-derives pk from sk internally and compares, and any
  mismatch aborts via `unreachable` (rethrown by the TypeScript
  wrapper as `SigningError('sig-malformed-input', ...)`). The
  defence costs one extra Edwards scalar multiplication per sign,
  roughly 5ms at parameter-set sizes.

  Initialize via `init({ ed25519: ... })` or the alias
  `init({ x25519: ... })`; both resolve to the underlying
  `curve25519` slot, and the init layer de-dupes when given
  identical sources. Subpath exports:
  `leviathan-crypto/ed25519`. The full RFC 8032 §7 test corpus
  plus the NIST ACVP EDDSA keyGen / sigGen / sigVer records
  verify byte-for-byte. Every WASM region holding a
  secret-derived intermediate (clamped scalar a, signing prefix,
  per-signature r and k, the Edwards points A and R) is wiped on
  every success and failure path.

- **X25519.** RFC 7748 Curve25519 Diffie-Hellman lands as the
  first classical key-agreement primitive. The new `X25519`
  class exposes `keygen`, `keygenDerand(sk)`, and `dh(sk,
  peerPk)`. Clamping (RFC 7748 §5, The X25519 and X448
  Functions) happens internally on every call; the stored
  secretKey is the unclamped form so round-tripping preserves
  byte-equality. The substrate's `feFromBytes` masks bit 255 of
  the peer pk internally, so callers pass the encoded
  u-coordinate byte-for-byte.

  Per RFC 7748 §6.1, Curve25519, a small-order peer pk produces
  an all-zero shared secret that carries no contributory entropy
  from the local secret. The TypeScript layer rejects with a
  new `KeyAgreementError` after a constant-time OR-accumulate
  scan across the 32 output bytes; the throw fires only after
  the full accumulator is known, so the success path is
  constant-time and the rejection branches off only on a
  known-bad outcome. The WASM substrate itself is filter-free
  so any vector that exercises a small-order peer pk verifies
  byte-for-byte at the WASM boundary; the TS-layer rejection is
  the public API contract. This matches the x25519-dalek
  posture.

  Initialize via `init({ x25519: ... })` or the alias
  `init({ ed25519: ... })`. Subpath exports:
  `leviathan-crypto/x25519`. The RFC 7748 §6.1, Curve25519,
  Alice/Bob vectors plus the §5 iter=1 and iter=1000 chain
  records verify byte-for-byte; the iter=1,000,000 record is
  deferred to manual verification per `vector_audit.md`.

- **curve25519.wasm.** The eleventh WASM binary lands as a
  scalar (no v128) module hosting the substrate for both Ed25519
  and X25519. The module provides GF(2^255-19) field arithmetic
  at radix-2^51, the edwards25519 point operations in extended
  coordinates, the X25519 Montgomery ladder, the scalar
  arithmetic mod L, and point compression with strict-canonical
  decompression. The dalek parallel-formulas approach (eprint
  2018/098) only pays off with a native paired 64x64-to-128
  multiply, which AssemblyScript's v128 instruction set does not
  expose; the emulated path through `i64x2.extmul_*` is not
  measurably faster than two sequential scalar `feMul` calls, so
  the module ships scalar.

  An embedded SHA-512 ported verbatim from
  `src/asm/sha2/sha512.ts` keeps the Ed25519 hash chain inside a
  single WASM call rather than crossing the JS/WASM boundary 6
  to 12 times per signature for sha2 orchestration. The
  embedded copy is module-internal; the curve25519 ABI does not
  surface a sha512* function. Source-pin commit recorded in the
  `sha512.ts` header; future audits re-diff against
  `src/asm/sha2/sha512.ts`.

  Module identity: `getModuleId() = 8`. Memory: 4 pages
  (262144 bytes), mutable footprint under 4 KB. The TypeScript
  layer claims the region above `BUFFER_END` as the I/O staging
  region for caller-supplied inputs and outputs; the WASM never
  reads or writes that region. The 4-page sizing gives the
  pure-mode `Ed25519Suite` a per-call message ceiling of
  approximately 248 KB; messages above the ceiling throw
  `RangeError`. Pure-mode signatures are non-streamable by
  design; larger payloads use `Ed25519PreHashSuite` plus
  `SignStream` / `VerifyStream`, which compute SHA-512 at the
  TypeScript layer and only stage the 64-byte digest in WASM.

- **Ed25519Suite and Ed25519PreHashSuite.** Two new
  SignatureSuite consts wrap Ed25519 into the v3 sign envelope.
  `Ed25519Suite` (format byte `0x01`) covers pure Ed25519 and
  satisfies `SignatureSuite` only; the suite rejects non-empty
  user_ctx with `SigningError('sig-ctx-unsupported')` because
  pure Ed25519 has no spec-defined home for ctx, and routes
  callers to `Ed25519PreHashSuite` for context-bound signatures.
  `Ed25519PreHashSuite` (format byte `0x11`) covers Ed25519ph,
  pins the prehash algorithm to SHA-512, and satisfies
  `StreamableSignatureSuite` so `SignStream` and `VerifyStream`
  accept it. The dom2(F=1, effective_ctx) binding happens inside
  the curve25519 WASM; the suite passes
  `buildEffectiveCtx(ctxDomain, user_ctx)` as the WASM ctx
  parameter.

  `Ed25519PreHashSuite.wasmModules` is `['curve25519', 'sha2']`
  because the message-taking `sign(msg)` path and the streaming
  prehash both drive the sha2 module's SHA-512 (the
  curve25519-embedded SHA-512 covers dom2 prefixing inside the
  WASM only). `Ed25519Suite.wasmModules` is `['curve25519']`
  alone. Per-call WASM lifecycle: each suite method
  instantiates a fresh `Ed25519` inside a `try / finally
  { dispose() }` block. KAT vectors live in
  `test/vectors/sign_ed25519.ts` and verify byte-for-byte
  against the third-party Ed25519 oracles per
  `vector_audit.md`.

- **KeyAgreementError.** New error class for the X25519
  surface. `X25519.dh` throws it when the shared secret is
  all-zero (peer pk is a small-order point on Curve25519). The
  class extends `Error` and exists specifically for this code
  path so callers can branch via `err instanceof
  KeyAgreementError` and distinguish a degenerate exchange from
  a caller-side contract violation (`TypeError` on non-
  `Uint8Array` inputs, `RangeError` on wrong-length inputs).

- **Phase 4 follow-up tightening (post-review).** Six review
  findings against the Phase 4 Ed25519 surface landed in a
  single coordinated pass. Each lands a rubric-shaped change
  Phase 5 (ECDSA-P256) and Phase 6 (classical+PQ hybrids) will
  copy when they start.

  - **Suite-layer sign refactor.** `Ed25519PureSuite.sign`,
    `Ed25519PrehashSuite.sign`, and
    `Ed25519PrehashSuite.signPrehashed` previously called
    `Ed25519.keygenDerand(sk)` followed by
    `Ed25519.sign(sk, derivedPk, msg)`, which paid one extra
    basepoint scalar multiplication per call. Two new WASM
    exports (`ed25519SignInternalPk`,
    `ed25519SignPrehashedInternalPk`) and unexported class
    helpers (`_signInternalPk`, `_signPrehashedInternalPk`)
    derive pk inside the same WASM call and skip the fault-
    injection cross-check. The cross-check is degenerate at the
    suite call site (both pk and the comparator come from the
    same call on the same module), so suite-level performance
    improves ~30% without changing the effective trust
    boundary. Direct `Ed25519.sign(sk, pk, msg)` callers
    continue to get the cross-check intact.

  - **`verifyPrehashed` digest-length contract.** Every shipped
    suite (`MlDsa*PreHashSuite`, `SlhDsa*PreHashSuite`,
    `Ed25519PreHashSuite`, the PQ-only hybrids) now throws
    `SigningError('sig-malformed-input')` on a wrong-length
    digest, symmetric with `signPrehashed`. Previously
    `verifyPrehashed` returned `false`; the asymmetry conflated
    a caller contract violation with a signature outcome and
    is the locked rule in `docs/signaturesuite.md`. The hybrid-
    pq factory keeps `pk.length` and `sig.length` on the soft-
    fail path (those bytes are wire-derived) and only flips the
    digest check.

  - **`Ed25519Suite` per-call message cap.** Pure-mode Ed25519
    cannot stream, and `curve25519.wasm` was previously sized
    at 2 pages, which gave the pure-mode message-staging region
    a ~120 KB ceiling that surfaced only as a deep
    `RangeError`. The module is now 4 pages (256 KB), raising
    the ceiling to approximately 248 KB. The cap is documented
    loudly in `docs/ed25519.md`, `docs/signaturesuite.md`, and
    the `Ed25519Suite` JSDoc, with the recommended path
    (`Ed25519PreHashSuite` plus `SignStream`) called out.

  - **`sig-ctx-unsupported` discriminator catalogued.** The
    discriminator that `Ed25519Suite` already threw on non-empty
    user_ctx is now listed in
    `docs/signaturesuite.md`'s suite-layer discriminator table
    and `docs/ed25519.md`'s error reference. Pure-only suites
    that ship in later phases (Ed448 if it lands) reuse the
    same discriminator.

  - **`Ed25519.signPrehashed` ctx required.** The `ctx?`
    default-empty parameter on the public
    `Ed25519.signPrehashed(sk, pk, digest, ctx)` is dropped;
    callers must pass an explicit `Uint8Array` (use
    `new Uint8Array(0)` for no context binding). This matches
    the suite-layer "ctx is required" rule and removes a
    quietly-different shape between the class and suite APIs.

  - **`ed25519Wasm` / `x25519Wasm` aliases.** The
    `leviathan-crypto/ed25519/embedded` and
    `leviathan-crypto/x25519/embedded` subpaths now export the
    underlying curve25519 blob under three names:
    `curve25519Wasm` (canonical), `ed25519Wasm`, and
    `x25519Wasm` (aliases that read more naturally under each
    subpath). All three resolve to the identical string; tree-
    shaking is unaffected.

Migration: none. All additions; no breaking changes from the AES,
ML-DSA, or curve25519 landings. The v2 → v3 migration items above
(Serpent byte-order flip, ChaCha salamander defense) are the only
breaking changes in this release; the cipher suite, generator,
signature, classical-signature, key-agreement, and SP 800-185
additions add no migration burden.

### Breaking Changes

- **⚠ Serpent public byte-order convention flipped to NIST natural byte
  order.** v2 and earlier loaded a 16-byte block into internal words with
  bytes 15..12 in `r[0]`, the AES-submission floppy byte order. v3 loads
  bytes 0..3 into `r[0]` as a little-endian u32 with byte 0 as the LSB.
  This is the convention used by FIPS 197 (AES), AB&K's NESSIE submission
  of Serpent, the Wikipedia pseudocode, and the RustCrypto, Crypto++,
  Botan, and BouncyCastle implementations. v2 stood alone in the ecosystem
  on the floppy convention, and AB&K's own NESSIE submission already
  preferred the natural-order layout.

  **The wire format is incompatible.** v2 ciphertexts produced by
  `SerpentCipher`, `SerpentCbc`, or `SerpentCtr` cannot be decrypted by
  v3, and v3 ciphertexts cannot be decrypted by v2. There is no
  automated migration path. Persisted v2 ciphertexts must be decrypted
  under v2 and re-encrypted under v3. Consumers using only `Seal`,
  `SealStream`, `SealStreamPool`, or `OpenStream` see no API change.
  Only the wire bytes change.

  **The cipher math is unchanged.** S-boxes, linear transform, key
  schedule, and round count are byte identical to v2. Only the I/O
  convention at the public API boundary moved. The KAT corpus (NESSIE
  Set 1-8 across all three key sizes; NIST CAVP would behave identically
  if it covered Serpent) passes against the same expected hex values
  consumed unchanged.

  **The HKDF info string is bumped.** `serpent-sealstream-v2` →
  `serpent-sealstream-v3`. Two consequences: a v2 stream key cannot
  derive into a v3 derived-key set even on the same master key and
  nonce, and the info-string change provides a clean domain separator
  between the two wire formats so a misrouted v2 blob cannot
  authenticate under v3 keys.

  **Pinned KAT vector files renamed.** `seal_serpent_v2.ts` →
  `seal_serpent_v3.ts`, `sealstream_serpent_v2.ts` →
  `sealstream_serpent_v3.ts`. The TypeScript types
  (`SealSerpentV2Vector`, `SealStreamSerpentV2Vector`) became
  `SealSerpentV3Vector` and `SealStreamSerpentV3Vector`. The
  `serpent_ctr.ts` self-generated CTR vector file kept its name but its
  bytes were regenerated under the v3 cipher.

  **AES-submission KAT files unchanged.** The floppy-format KAT files
  shipped on the `floppy1` branch (`serpent_ecb_*.txt`,
  `serpent_cbc_*.txt`) remain in `test/vectors/` byte-identical. v3
  consumes them via byte-reversal preprocessing at the test-helper
  boundary (`test/unit/helpers.ts`, `test/unit/serpent/vector_parser.ts`).
  The reversal lives in TypeScript test code, not in the WASM. The
  NESSIE files (`serpent_nessie-*.txt`) feed straight through without
  reversal, since they were already in NIST natural byte order.

  **Why now.** v3 is the first release where the wire format is allowed
  to break: the ChaCha salamander-resistance fix already invalidated v2
  XChaCha sealstream output, AES landed alongside Serpent and uses NIST
  natural byte order natively, and the project has not yet hit 1.0
  semantic-version stability for its wire format. Aligning Serpent with
  AES, with AB&K's submission preference, and with the rest of the
  ecosystem now avoids carrying a single-cipher convention mismatch
  forward indefinitely.

  Migration:

  | scenario | action |
  |---|---|
  | `Seal`, `SealStream`, `SealStreamPool`, `OpenStream` consumers | none. API unchanged; only wire bytes change. Re-encrypt persisted blobs. |
  | `SerpentCbc`, `SerpentCtr` consumers | none in API. Re-encrypt persisted ciphertexts under v3. |
  | Consumers passing v2 hex KAT bytes through `SerpentCbc.decrypt` | reverse all 16 bytes of each block, or regenerate under v3. |
  | Cross-language interop with RustCrypto / Crypto++ / Botan / BouncyCastle | now works without byte-reversal. v2 required reversal at the boundary. |


- **⚠ `_<module>Ready` probes removed.** The five low-level readiness probes
  (`_serpentReady`, `_chachaReady`, `_sha2Ready`, `_sha3Ready`, `_kyberReady`)
  are gone from both type and runtime exports, submodule definitions deleted,
  root barrel re-exports stripped. They were a redundant parallel API to the
  already-public `isInitialized(mod: Module): boolean` helper exported from
  the root barrel and from each submodule. The underscore-prefixed names were
  never part of the documented public surface; they only appeared in
  `docs/architecture.md` as part of the export map, never in user-facing API
  docs. Removed without a deprecation window, one source of truth from this
  release forward.

  Migration is mechanical:

  | before                 | after                          |
  |------------------------|--------------------------------|
  | `_serpentReady()`      | `isInitialized('serpent')`     |
  | `_chachaReady()`       | `isInitialized('chacha20')`    |
  | `_sha2Ready()`         | `isInitialized('sha2')`        |
  | `_sha3Ready()`         | `isInitialized('sha3')`        |
  | `_kyberReady()`        | `isInitialized('kyber')`       |

  Update the import: `import { isInitialized } from 'leviathan-crypto'`.

  Note one semantic narrowing: `_kyberReady()` previously checked **both** the
  `kyber` and `sha3` modules (kyber depends on SHAKE for its KDF/PRF). The
  replacement `isInitialized('kyber')` checks only the `kyber` module. If the
  combined check matters, do `isInitialized('kyber') && isInitialized('sha3')`.
  In practice every code path that uses MlKem* classes touches a sha3-backed
  init separately, so the strict combined check is rare outside of test code.

  This removal also resolves a v2.1.0 packaging bug, `_serpentReady` and
  `_chachaReady` were missing from `dist/serpent/index.d.ts` and
  `dist/chacha20/index.d.ts` because their source declarations carried
  `@internal` while the root barrel re-exported them by name, so downstream
  `tsc --noEmit` failed to resolve the re-export. The bug dissolves with the
  symbols themselves; no per-symbol fix needed.

- **`isInitialized(mod)` now re-exported from every submodule subpath.**
  Previously only the root barrel and the kyber subpath re-exported it.
  Tree-shake-friendly imports can now do
  `import { serpentInit, isInitialized } from 'leviathan-crypto/serpent'`
  in a single line. Purely additive on the seven other submodule subpaths
  (serpent, chacha20, sha2, sha3, keccak, stream, ratchet); kyber's
  existing re-export is unchanged.

### Test Suite

- **`internal-api-stripped.test.ts` invariant inverted for the five probes.**
  Previously asserted "Public `_<module>Ready` probes survive" via a
  string-presence check on `dist/index.d.ts` (which was satisfied by the
  re-export line itself regardless of resolution, the test passed even
  against the broken 2.1.0 build). Now asserts full removal across
  `dist/index.d.ts`, `dist/index.js`, and each submodule
  `dist/<mod>/index.d.ts` and `dist/<mod>/index.js`. Adds positive controls
  on `isInitialized` to confirm the replacement is exported. Docstring
  rewritten to document the post-2.1.1 contract.

- **`init.test.ts` migrated.** All `_<module>Ready()` call sites swapped to
  `isInitialized('<module>')`.

### Documentation

- `docs/CLAUDE_consumer.md` adds a "Probing initialization state" section
  documenting `isInitialized(mod)` as the canonical readiness probe, with a
  note that the per-module `_<module>Ready()` probes were removed in 2.1.1.
  Full API reference remains in `docs/init.md`.

- `docs/architecture.md` per-submodule export map drops the `_<module>Ready`
  entries for serpent, chacha20, sha2, and sha3 (kyber's row never listed it).

- `docs/test-suite.md` updated to describe the inverted invariant and the new
  test count (10 → 21).

- `docs/architecture.md` picks up the `ratchet/index.ts` row (added in v2.1.0
  but never recorded in the export map), `kyberInit` in the subpath-init list,
  and a footnote noting that `isInitialized(mod)` is now reachable from every
  submodule subpath.

- `docs/cdn.md` examples no longer hardcode the package version, non-SRI
  URLs are unversioned (resolved by unpkg's redirect to the latest release)
  so the doc stops needing a sed-pass at every version bump. The SRI example
  keeps an explicit version pin since the integrity hash is bytes-specific.
  Added a "Pinning" callout at the top recommending pinned versions for
  production. The "WASM filenames" table picks up a missing `kyber.wasm` row.

### Internal

- **`loader.ts` exports tagged `@internal`.** The three loader functions
  (`decodeWasm`, `compileWasm`, `loadWasm`) now strip from the published
  `dist/loader.d.ts`, matching `docs/loader.md`'s long-standing claim that
  the module is internal. The `_depth` recursion-guard parameter on
  `compileWasm` was renamed to `depth` since the underscore signal is
  redundant once the function is type-private. No runtime change; internal
  callers (`init.ts`, `seal-stream-pool.ts`) and tests are unaffected
  (relative source imports, not the published `.d.ts`).

### Added (Phase 1 signature work)

- **`Sign`, `SignStream`, `VerifyStream`** under `src/ts/sign/`. `Sign` is the
  single-shot envelope (`Sign.sign`, `Sign.verify`, `Sign.signDetached`,
  `Sign.verifyDetached`, `Sign.peek`), structurally parallel to `Seal`.
  `SignStream` and `VerifyStream` are the streaming counterparts; the wire
  bytes produced by `SignStream.finalize` are byte-identical to `Sign.sign`
  for the same `(suite, sk, msg, ctx)`, so production and consumption sides
  can choose independently between in-memory and incremental.
- **SignatureSuite abstraction.** `SignatureSuite` and the
  `StreamableSignatureSuite` extension are the structural template for every
  signature scheme the lib ships now and in the future, parallel to
  `CipherSuite` in the seal layer. `PrehashAlgorithm` is the union of the six
  prehash function identifiers used across the catalog. All three are
  exported from the top-level barrel.
- **Six ML-DSA-backed suite consts.** `MlDsa44Suite`, `MlDsa65Suite`, and
  `MlDsa87Suite` (catalog bytes 0x03, 0x04, 0x05) cover pure ML-DSA across
  NIST security categories 2/3/5. `MlDsa44PreHashSuite`, `MlDsa65PreHashSuite`,
  and `MlDsa87PreHashSuite` (catalog bytes 0x13, 0x14, 0x15) cover the
  HashML-DSA variants. Prehash choices: SHA3-256 for the 44 / 65 levels,
  SHA3-512 for the 87 level. Every suite ships a built-in
  `{scheme}-envelope-v3` (or `{scheme}-prehash-envelope-v3`) ctxDomain so
  signatures cannot accidentally validate across suites even with identical
  `(sk, msg, user_ctx)`.
- **`SigningError`** class in `src/ts/errors.ts`. Discriminator-first
  constructor mirroring `AuthenticationError`'s posture: 12 stable
  discriminator strings span the suite layer (`sig-key-size`,
  `sig-ctx-too-long`, `sig-malformed-input`), the envelope layer
  (`sig-blob-too-short`, `sig-suite-unknown`, `sig-ctx-overflow`,
  `sig-ctx-mismatch`, `verify-failed`), and the stream layer
  (`sig-stream-finalized`, `sig-stream-disposed`, `sig-suite-mismatch`).
- **`MlDsaBase` prehashed-input surface.** Four new methods accept a
  precomputed prehash digest rather than re-hashing the message:
  `signHashPrehashed`, `signHashPrehashedDeterministic`,
  `signHashPrehashedDerand`, and `verifyHashPrehashed`. M' construction
  (OID prefix plus ctx plus PH) is shared with the existing `signHash` /
  `verifyHash`, only the digest source changes. `SignStream` and
  `VerifyStream` build on these so a streamed prehash flow is byte-identical
  to a single-shot one whose digest was computed externally.
- **`SHA3_256Stream` and `SHA3_512Stream`** in the sha3 module. Incremental
  SHA-3 over `update(chunk)` / `finalize()`, lifecycle modeled after
  SHAKE128: `_acquireModule('sha3')` at construction, `_releaseModule` on
  `finalize()` or `dispose()`, the same exclusivity guard that protects
  SHAKE state. Required by `SignStream` for prehash suites; usable on their
  own anywhere a fixed-output streamed SHA-3 digest is needed.
- **`docs/signaturesuite.md`** spec doc parallel to `docs/ciphersuite.md`,
  documenting the SignatureSuite interface, the 22-entry format-byte
  catalog (with Phase 1 entries 0x03-0x05 and 0x13-0x15 live), the wire
  format, the ctxDomain construction rules, and the error discriminator
  table.
- **`docs/phase-index.md`** tracking the seven-phase v3 signature roadmap.
  Phase 1 marked complete; Phases 2 through 7 marked queued with their
  owned files and dependencies.

Migration: none. All additions, no breaking changes.

### Added (Phase 2 signature work, SLH-DSA + PQ-only hybrids)

- **SLH-DSA primitive.** FIPS 205 Stateless Hash-Based Digital Signature
  Standard ships as the second post-quantum signature scheme in the
  library. Three classes, `SlhDsa128f`, `SlhDsa192f`, `SlhDsa256f`
  (SHAKE-family fast parameter sets, NIST security categories 1/3/5),
  share one `slhdsa` WASM module. Pure SLH-DSA exposes `keygen` /
  `keygenDerand`, hedged `sign` (FIPS 205 §3.4 recommended default),
  `signDeterministic`, `signDerand` (CAVP / externally-supplied opt_rand),
  and `verify`. HashSLH-DSA (FIPS 205 §10.2.2) exposes `signHash` /
  `signHashDeterministic` / `signHashDerand` / `verifyHash` and the
  caller-supplied-prehash counterparts `signHashPrehashed` /
  `signHashPrehashedDeterministic` / `signHashPrehashedDerand` /
  `verifyHashPrehashed`. The pre-hash domain separator byte (0x01) plus
  the per-function OID DER bytes from NIST CSOR enforce cross-protocol
  domain separation, signatures from `signHash` cannot verify under
  `verify` on the same key (FIPS 205 §10.2 narrative). The category-1
  restriction on SHA2-256 / SHAKE128 prehash (§10.2.2) is enforced at
  the public surface.

  Initialize via `init({ slhdsa: slhdsaWasm })`; HashSLH-DSA with a SHA-2
  family pre-hash additionally requires `init({ sha2: sha2Wasm })`; SHA-3
  or SHAKE pre-hashes additionally require `init({ sha3: sha3Wasm })`.
  Subpath exports: `leviathan-crypto/slhdsa` and
  `leviathan-crypto/slhdsa/embedded`. The slhdsa WASM module embeds its
  own Keccak permutation (verbatim port from sha3-wasm) for the internal
  F / H / T_l / PRF / PRFmsg / Hmsg primitives, so pure-SLH-DSA usage
  never touches the sha3 module. The ACVP corpus (keyGen / sigGen /
  sigVer across all three parameter sets, hedged plus deterministic plus
  derand modes) is byte-identical to the published vectors. Every WASM
  region holding a secret or secret-derived intermediate is wiped on the
  way out (success and failure paths).

- **Six SLH-DSA suite consts.** `SlhDsa128fSuite`, `SlhDsa192fSuite`,
  `SlhDsa256fSuite` (catalog bytes 0x06, 0x07, 0x08) cover pure SLH-DSA
  across the three SHAKE-family fast parameter sets.
  `SlhDsa128fPreHashSuite`, `SlhDsa192fPreHashSuite`,
  `SlhDsa256fPreHashSuite` (catalog bytes 0x16, 0x17, 0x18) cover the
  HashSLH-DSA prehash variants. Prehash choices: SHAKE128 (32-byte
  digest) for the 128f level, SHAKE256 (64-byte digest) for 192f and
  256f, the category-appropriate algorithms per FIPS 205 §10.2.2. Every
  suite ships a built-in `slhdsa{Nnnf}-envelope-v3` (or
  `slhdsa{Nnnf}-prehash-envelope-v3`) ctxDomain so signatures cannot
  accidentally validate across suites even with identical
  `(sk, msg, user_ctx)`.

- **Three PQ-only hybrid suite consts.** `MlDsa44SlhDsa128fSuite`,
  `MlDsa65SlhDsa192fSuite`, `MlDsa87SlhDsa256fSuite` (catalog bytes
  0x30, 0x31, 0x32) compose ML-DSA and SLH-DSA at matching NIST security
  categories (2+1, 3+3, 5+5). Composite encoding is
  `pk_combined = pk_mldsa || pk_slhdsa` and
  `sig_combined = sig_mldsa || sig_slhdsa` with sizes catalog-known and
  no length prefixes. ML-DSA-first ordering by convention. Both
  sub-signers receive the same `effective_ctx`; the per-hybrid
  `mldsa{XX}-slhdsa{YYY}f-envelope-v3` ctxDomain blocks cross-suite and
  cross-hybrid forgery (a standalone `MlDsa44Suite` sig placed as the
  ML-DSA half of a 0x30 hybrid is rejected). `verifyPrehashed` always
  runs both sub-verifies (no early return on the first half's boolean).
  Streaming via `SignStream` / `VerifyStream` is mandatory: hybrids are
  prehash-only (the SHAKE digest is hashed once and fed to both halves).
  All three hybrids declare `wasmModules: ['mldsa', 'sha3', 'slhdsa']`.

- **`SHAKE128Stream` and `SHAKE256Stream`** in the sha3 module.
  Fixed-output streaming SHAKE variants matching the `RunningHash`
  contract used by `SignStream` / `VerifyStream`. `outputLen` is bound
  at construction; `update(chunk)` absorbs, `finalize()` pads and
  squeezes exactly `outputLen` bytes then disposes the instance.
  Lifecycle mirrors `SHA3_256Stream` / `SHAKE128`: `_acquireModule('sha3')`
  at construction, `_releaseModule` on `finalize()` / `dispose()`, the
  same exclusivity guard that protects SHAKE state. The multi-squeeze
  `SHAKE128` / `SHAKE256` classes remain for the XOF surface; the new
  Stream classes are the fixed-output cousins. Required by
  `createRunningHash` for SLH-DSA and PQ-only hybrid prehash suites.

- **`'shake-128'` and `'shake-256'`** cases in `createRunningHash`. The
  Phase 1 dispatcher in `src/ts/sign/hasher.ts` previously wired only
  `'sha3-256'` / `'sha3-512'`; the two SHAKE entries now route to
  `SHAKE128Stream(32)` and `SHAKE256Stream(64)` so the
  `StreamableSignatureSuite` declarations on SLH-DSA prehash and PQ-only
  hybrid suites are satisfied end-to-end. The SHA-2 dispatch still
  throws, those land in Phase 4 (Ed25519ph) / Phase 5 (ECDSA-P256
  prehash).

- **`--cipher slhdsa` and `--cipher hybrid-pq`** in the independent Rust
  verifier (`scripts/verify-vectors`). The slhdsa dispatcher cross-checks
  the ACVP keyGen / sigGen / sigVer corpora against a separate-lineage
  Rust `slh-dsa` crate; the hybrid-pq dispatcher decomposes composite
  pk / sig pairs and verifies each half independently to confirm the
  composite encoding is sound at both ends. Both run in the default
  `--cipher all --target all` corpus walk, so every PR exercises the new
  vectors end-to-end against an independent oracle.

- **Docs.** `docs/slhdsa.md` (full SLH-DSA API reference); `docs/slhdsa_audit.md`
  (xero-reviewed audit doc, internal to the repo, not shipped in the npm
  package); a PQ-only hybrid composite-encoding section in
  `docs/signaturesuite.md`; a PQ-only hybrid threat-model section in
  `SECURITY.md`; the SLH-DSA layer addition in `docs/architecture.md`.

Migration: none. All additions, no breaking changes. The Phase 1 ML-DSA
surface (six suites, `Sign` / `SignStream` / `VerifyStream`,
`MlDsa{44,65,87}` classes) is unchanged.

### Added (Phase 3 signature work, BLAKE3 hash substrate)

- **BLAKE3 substrate.** [BLAKE3](https://github.com/BLAKE3-team/BLAKE3-specs)
  ships as the tenth WASM binary (`blake3.wasm`, 2 memory pages) and the
  third hash family in the library, peer to SHA-2 and SHA-3. All three
  modes from the spec are implemented: default-mode hash (§2.5),
  keyed_hash with a 32-byte key (§2.6), and the two-pass derive_key
  (§2.7) for context-bound KDF use. The §2.5 unbounded XOF reader sits
  on top of every streaming class; `finalizeXof()` returns a
  `BLAKE3OutputReader` that lifts 64-byte blocks off a root-state
  snapshot via the WASM `squeezeXofBlock` export until the caller stops
  reading or disposes the reader.

  Initialize via `init({ blake3: blake3Wasm })`. SIMD-only, joins
  serpent / chacha20 / aes / kyber / mldsa in the v128-required tier;
  the init preflight rejects when WebAssembly SIMD is unavailable.
  Subpath exports: `leviathan-crypto/blake3` and
  `leviathan-crypto/blake3/embedded`.

- **v128 SIMD compression kernels.** The module ships two:
  `compress` is the v128-internal single-state §2.2 compression
  function used everywhere a single chunk or parent node is hashed,
  and `compress4` is the v128-external lane-parallel form (lane K =
  compress operation K) that runs four independent compress operations
  in parallel across distinct CVs, messages, counters, and block_lens.
  Tree-mode chunk and parent hashing dispatches to `compress4` whenever
  four siblings are available; the streaming classes' fallback path
  uses `compress1`. There is no scalar fallback.

- **Seven public classes plus one HashFn const.** `BLAKE3`,
  `BLAKE3KeyedHash`, `BLAKE3DeriveKey` are the one-shot
  (`hash` / `derive`) atomic entries; `BLAKE3Stream`,
  `BLAKE3KeyedHashStream`, `BLAKE3DeriveKeyStream` are the streaming
  counterparts (`update` / `finalize` / `finalizeXof` / `dispose`);
  `BLAKE3OutputReader` is the XOF reader returned by `finalizeXof()`.
  `BLAKE3Hash` is a stateless 32-byte `HashFn` const compatible with
  the `Fortuna` accumulator slot, peer to `SHA256Hash` and
  `SHA3_256Hash`. Streaming classes hold the blake3 module
  exclusively from construction until `finalize()` / `finalizeXof()` /
  `dispose()` (same exclusivity discipline as `SHA3_256Stream` /
  `SHAKE128Stream`).

- **Tree-mode internal exports as Phase 7 substrate.** The WASM
  module exposes `_testChunkCV`, `_testParentCV`, and
  `_testDeriveContextCV` for the tree-internals unit test surface and
  the planned `src/ts/merkle/blake3-log.ts` log-proof substrate that
  Phase 7 (Merkle log + STH) builds on. These are NOT part of the
  consumer-facing `Blake3Exports` interface; the underscore prefix and
  `@internal` tag keep them out of the published `.d.ts`.

- **35-record upstream KAT corpus.** The full BLAKE3-team
  [test_vectors.json](https://github.com/BLAKE3-team/BLAKE3/blob/master/test_vectors/test_vectors.json)
  corpus (input lengths 0..102400 covering every chunk and CV-stack
  boundary the §2.3 / §2.4 design exercises) is checked into
  `test/vectors/blake3.ts` and replayed under all three modes against
  one-shot, streaming, and full 131-byte XOF paths. The Rust verifier
  (`scripts/verify-vectors`) gains a `--cipher blake3` dispatcher
  that cross-checks the corpus against the upstream `blake3` crate as
  an independent oracle; a `scripts/verify-vectors/src/bin/gen_blake3_large.rs`
  helper pre-computes the three large-input cross-check expectations
  (8 KB / 64 KiB / 100 KB) the unit suite uses outside the KAT range.

- **CI test group.** BLAKE3 primitive tests live in the `blake3` CI
  group in `scripts/lib/test-groups.ts` (5-min timeout, `UNIT_BASE`
  build targets). The group covers the §2.2 compress KAT gate, the
  upstream corpus across all three modes, compress4-vs-compress1
  randomized equivalence, the tree-internals test surface, streaming-
  vs-one-shot equivalence, full 131-byte XOF output across the 105
  (35 × 3 modes) corpus replay, large-input cross-check vs the Rust
  oracle, dispose-time wipe coverage, and every TS validation throw
  path.

- **Docs.** `docs/blake3.md` (full BLAKE3 API reference, ships in the
  npm doc bundle via `scripts/copy-docs.ts`); `docs/blake3_audit.md`
  (xero-reviewed audit doc, internal to the repo, not shipped in the
  npm package); the BLAKE3 module addition in `docs/architecture.md`
  and `docs/lexicon.md`. Routing row added to `docs/CLAUDE_consumer.md`
  so consumer agents pick up the new primitive family. Phase 3 of the
  v3 signature work plan is now complete; `docs/phase-index.md` flips
  Phase 3 to ✅.

Migration: none. All additions, no breaking changes. The Phase 1 / 2
signature surface is unchanged. BLAKE3 sits alongside SHA-2 and SHA-3
in the hash tier and feeds the Phase 7 Merkle log substrate when that
phase opens.

### Added (Phase 5 signature work, ECDSA-P256)

- **ECDSA over NIST P-256.** Classical ECDSA per FIPS 186-5 §6,
  ECDSA Signature Algorithm, over the NIST P-256 curve from
  SP 800-186 §3.2.1.3, lands as the second classical signature
  primitive in the library (peer to Ed25519). The new `EcdsaP256`
  class covers `keygen()` / `keygenDerand(seed)`,
  `sign(sk, pk, msgHash, rnd)` with the fault-injection
  cross-check intact, the suite-only `_signInternalPk(sk, msgHash,
  rnd)` helper that skips the cross-check, `verify(pk, msgHash,
  sig)`, and `dispose()`. The class consumes a 32-byte SHA-256
  digest rather than a raw message; the suite layer drives
  SHA-256 on top.

  K derivation supports both modes from the spec: pure-
  deterministic per RFC 6979 §3.2 when `rnd` is all-zero, and
  hedged-deterministic per `draft-irtf-cfrg-det-sigs-with-noise-05`
  §4 when `rnd` is non-zero. The two are intentionally NOT
  byte-equivalent on all-zero `rnd` per the draft's domain
  separation; the all-zero shortcut routes through the verbatim
  RFC 6979 path so RFC 6979 §A.2.5 vectors reproduce
  byte-for-byte. Signer normalises `s` to low-S per RFC 6979 §3.5
  on both code paths; verifier rejects high-S as part of the
  leviathan-crypto strict-gate posture.

  Verification is strict per leviathan-crypto convention: pk
  decompression failure, identity-element pk, `r` or `s` outside
  `[1, n-1]`, high-S, and signature-equation mismatch all return
  `false`. Caller-contract violations (wrong-length inputs)
  throw. The fault-injection defence on the public `sign` entry
  re-derives pk from sk inside the same WASM call and aborts via
  `unreachable` on mismatch against the caller-supplied pk;
  `_signInternalPk` skips the comparison for suite-layer callers
  whose comparator would otherwise come from the same potentially-
  faulted module.

  Initialise via `init({ p256: p256Wasm })`. Subpath exports:
  `leviathan-crypto/ecdsa` and `leviathan-crypto/ecdsa/embedded`
  (the embedded subpath exports the same blob under two names,
  `p256Wasm` canonical and `ecdsaP256Wasm` alias). The full
  RFC 6979 §A.2.5 + NIST ACVP ECDSA-FIPS186-5 keyGen / sigGen /
  sigVer + C2SP Wycheproof `ecdsa_secp256r1_sha256_p1363`
  corpora verify byte-for-byte. Every WASM region holding a
  secret-derived intermediate (scalar d, per-call nonce k,
  HMAC-DRBG K / V state, embedded SHA-256 streaming state,
  per-call rnd) is wiped on every success and failure path.

- **`EcdsaP256Suite`.** New `StreamableSignatureSuite` const
  wraps ECDSA-P256 into the v3 sign envelope at format byte
  `0x02`. The suite carries `ctxDomain:
  'ecdsa-p256-envelope-v3'` for `formatName` and display
  purposes but rejects every non-empty `user_ctx` with
  `SigningError('sig-ctx-unsupported')` because FIPS 186-5
  §6.4, ECDSA Signature Generation, has no native ctx
  parameter; context-bound ECDSA-P256 lives in the
  classical+PQ hybrid suites at `0x22` / `0x23` (reserved).
  `prehashAlgorithm: 'sha-256'`, `prehashSize: 32` are
  constants; the message-taking `sign(msg)` / `verify(msg)`
  paths route through `sha256OneShot` from
  `src/ts/sign/hasher.ts`, and the `SignStream` / `VerifyStream`
  paths route through a buffered `sha256Buffered` shim over
  the one-shot `SHA256` class (chunks copied and concatenated
  at `finalize()`, byte-identical to a one-shot SHA-256 over
  the full message).

  Suite-level sign is hedged-by-default per
  `draft-irtf-cfrg-det-sigs-with-noise-05`: every call
  generates `rnd = randomBytes(32)`, threads it through
  `EcdsaP256._signInternalPk`, and wipes the buffer in
  `finally`. Two suite-level signs of the same `(sk, msg)`
  return DIFFERENT signatures; both verify under the same pk.
  Consumers who need byte-deterministic signatures (RFC 6979
  §3.2 with empty entropy) must drop down to `EcdsaP256`
  directly with `rnd = new Uint8Array(32)`; the suite layer
  does not expose that knob.

  Wire format is the standard v3 attached envelope with
  `ctx_len = 0` (the suite locks ctx to empty); the 64-byte
  `r || s` signature is appended after the payload. Per-call
  WASM lifecycle: every suite method instantiates a fresh
  `EcdsaP256` inside a `try / finally { dispose() }` block.
  `wasmModules` is `['p256', 'sha2']`.

- **`ecdsaSignatureToDer` / `ecdsaSignatureFromDer`.** Strict-DER
  codec exposed at the root barrel for X.509 / JWS / TLS
  interop per RFC 3279 §2.2.3, ECDSA Signature Algorithm
  (`Ecdsa-Sig-Value ::= SEQUENCE { r INTEGER, s INTEGER }`).
  The encoder strips leading zero bytes to the minimal X.690
  §8.3.2 encoding and inserts a 0x00 sign-pad when the first
  content byte has the high bit set so the INTEGER decodes as
  positive; output length is 8..72 bytes. The decoder is strict
  DER (not BER) and rejects non-minimal length encodings,
  excess leading zero bytes, negative INTEGERs (high bit set
  without a sign-pad), INTEGER content longer than 33 bytes,
  trailing bytes after the outer SEQUENCE, and wrong tags
  (outer 0x30 SEQUENCE, inner 0x02 INTEGER) via
  `SigningError('sig-malformed-input')`. Semantic value
  rejections (`r = 0`, `s = 0`, high-s, off-range) are
  deferred to the WASM verify path. The library is zero-
  dependency, so the codec is hand-rolled rather than pulled
  from an external ASN.1 parser.

- **`p256.wasm` module (twelfth WASM binary).** New module ID
  9, 3 memory pages (196608 bytes), scalar (no v128). The
  Solinas reduction is a fixed sequence of nine limb-shuffling
  terms; lane packing buys nothing because every term touches
  a different subset of source limbs, the same WASM-extmul
  rationale that motivates curve25519's scalar choice. The
  module hosts: GF(p256) field arithmetic at 8 × u32 saturated
  radix-2^32 with HMV §2.4.1 Algorithm 2.27 Solinas reduction,
  scalar arithmetic mod n via bit-by-bit binary division,
  projective short-Weierstrass points `(X:Y:Z)` (96 bytes
  each), Renes-Costello-Batina 2016 complete addition formulas
  (Algorithm 4 add, Algorithm 6 double, specialised for
  `a = -3`), constant-time double-and-add-always scalar
  multiplication for both variable and fixed bases, an
  embedded SHA-256 ported verbatim from
  `src/asm/sha2/sha256.ts`, an embedded HMAC-SHA-256 ported
  verbatim from `src/asm/sha2/hmac.ts` (both module-internal,
  not exposed at the WASM ABI), and the four high-level
  ECDSA entry points: `ecdsaKeygen`, `ecdsaSign`,
  `ecdsaSignInternalPk`, `ecdsaVerify`. Mutable footprint
  under 4 KB; the remainder of the 3-page allocation is the
  TypeScript layer's I/O staging region.

- **Embedded SHA-256 + HMAC-SHA-256.** The RFC 6979 §3.2
  K-derivation runs through internal hash primitives so every
  signing operation stays inside a single WASM call rather
  than crossing the JS/WASM boundary tens of times per
  HMAC-DRBG chain iteration. Permitted deviations from the
  sha2-module source pin: buffer-offset imports rewritten to
  `./buffers` (p256 local memory layout, offset constant NAMES
  preserved), SHA-224 IVs and entry points stripped (P-256 +
  SHA-256 is the only consumer), a module-internal
  `sha256UpdateBytes(src, len)` helper appended for chunked
  updates over arbitrary memory offsets. The embedded copies
  are NOT re-exported from `src/asm/p256/index.ts`; the public
  ABI exposes ECDSA sign / verify only, mirroring curve25519's
  embedded-SHA-512 posture.

- **`sha-256` slot in `src/ts/sign/hasher.ts`.** The
  `PrehashAlgorithm` dispatch in `createRunningHash` now
  returns a buffered shim (`sha256Buffered`) over the one-shot
  `SHA256` class for the `'sha-256'` arm, mirroring the
  Phase 4 `sha512Buffered` posture. The shim copies chunks
  (so caller-owned buffers can be wiped under it) and
  concatenates at `finalize()` before driving the sha2 WASM
  module; the output is byte-identical to a one-shot SHA-256
  over the concatenated message. A streaming `SHA256Stream`
  class on the sha2 module was deliberately NOT created;
  ECDSA-P256ph is single-variant and the buffered shim is
  byte-equivalent at finalize.

- **Tier 1 vector corpus.** Five new vector files in
  `test/vectors/`: `ecdsa_p256.ts` (RFC 6979 §A.2.5
  deterministic-K gate, 2 records hand-transcribed from the
  RFC text), `ecdsa_p256_keygen.ts` (ACVP ECDSA-KeyGen-FIPS186-5,
  6 P-256 records across `testing candidates` plus `extra bits`
  modes), `ecdsa_p256_siggen.ts` (ACVP ECDSA-SigGen-FIPS186-5,
  10 P-256 SHA-256 records), `ecdsa_p256_sigver.ts` (ACVP
  ECDSA-SigVer-FIPS186-5, 7 P-256 SHA-256 records mixed
  pass / fail), and `ecdsa_p256_wycheproof.ts` (C2SP Wycheproof
  `ecdsa_secp256r1_sha256_p1363`, 262 records flattened from
  112 testGroups, raw r‖s wire shape). All five tracked by
  `test/vectors/SHA256SUMS`.

- **Tier 2 suite-level KAT corpus.** `test/vectors/sign_ecdsa_p256.ts`
  records suite-level envelope blobs covering empty / single-byte /
  64B / 1024B / RFC 6979 sample+test / 4096B messages, generated
  by the new `scripts/gen-ecdsa-p256-vectors.ts` and verified by
  the Rust crate. The corpus exercises `Sign.sign` / `Sign.verify`
  and the streaming `SignStream` / `VerifyStream` paths
  end-to-end.

- **Independent Rust verifier coverage.**
  `scripts/verify-vectors/src/ecdsa_p256.rs` is a new dispatcher
  that re-runs every ECDSA-P256 vector record against RustCrypto's
  `p256` + `ecdsa` crates as an independent oracle (separate
  lineage from leviathan-crypto's WASM stack). The verifier
  reads the five new vector files plus the suite-level Tier 2
  KAT and emits `✓ all vectors verified` on success. ACVP
  sigVer reconciliation accounts for leviathan-crypto's
  strict-S gate (the `p256` crate sets `NORMALIZE_S = false`
  and accepts high-S per FIPS 186-5 §6.4.4 verbatim); the
  Wycheproof corpus exercises the strict-gate directly.

- **New CI test groups.** `p256` and `ecdsa` for the substrate
  and TypeScript-class tests under `test/unit/p256/` and
  `test/unit/ecdsa/`. Sign-layer ECDSA-P256 tests
  (`test/unit/sign/sign-ecdsa-p256-*.test.ts`) live in the
  existing sign-layer group. The `.github/workflows/unit-p256.yml`
  workflow wires the p256 group into `test-suite.yml`.

- **Docs.** `docs/ecdsa-p256.md` (full ECDSA-P256 API reference,
  ships in the npm doc bundle via `scripts/copy-docs.ts`);
  `docs/ecdsa-p256_audit.md` (xero-reviewed audit doc, internal
  to the repo, not shipped in the npm package);
  `docs/asm_p256.md` (low-level WASM module reference);
  `docs/phase-index.md` (created; Phase 5 flipped to shipped,
  Phase 6 marked unblocked). The ECDSA-P256 module addition
  reflected in `docs/architecture.md`, `docs/signaturesuite.md`
  (catalog row `0x02` flipped from queued to shipped, full
  suite section added between Ed25519 and SLH-DSA pure-mode
  suites), `docs/init.md`, `docs/CLAUDE_consumer.md`,
  `docs/exports.md`, `docs/audits.md`, `docs/README.md`, and
  the root `README.md` Quick Start. AGENTS.md updated to
  reflect ECDSA-P256 as shipped in the per-call WASM lifecycle
  pattern note and the SHA-2 prehash slot note.

Migration: none. All additions, no breaking changes. The
Phase 1 / 2 / 3 / 4 signature surface is unchanged.
ECDSA-P256 sits alongside Ed25519 in the classical signature
tier and unblocks Phase 6 (BLAKE3-derived signature work) by
resolving the SHA-256 streaming-prehash slot in
`src/ts/sign/hasher.ts`.

- **Classical+PQ composite hybrid suites
  (`draft-ietf-lamps-pq-composite-sigs`).** Four new
  `StreamableSignatureSuite` consts at format bytes
  `0x20`-`0x23`: `MlDsa44Ed25519Suite`
  (`id-MLDSA44-Ed25519-SHA512`, OID `1.3.6.1.5.5.7.6.39`),
  `MlDsa65Ed25519Suite` (`id-MLDSA65-Ed25519-SHA512`, OID
  `1.3.6.1.5.5.7.6.48`), `MlDsa44EcdsaP256Suite`
  (`id-MLDSA44-ECDSA-P256-SHA256`, OID `1.3.6.1.5.5.7.6.40`),
  `MlDsa65EcdsaP256Suite` (`id-MLDSA65-ECDSA-P256-SHA512`,
  OID `1.3.6.1.5.5.7.6.45`). Each suite pre-hashes the
  message with its locked algorithm, builds the
  composite-sigs §3.2 `M' = Prefix || Label || len(ctx) || ctx
  || PH(M)` construction (32-byte ASCII Prefix
  `CompositeAlgorithmSignatures2025` per composite-sigs §2.2,
  per-suite Label per composite-sigs §6), and signs `M'` with
  both component primitives in parallel. The ML-DSA half uses
  pure ML-DSA (FIPS 204 §5.2 Algorithm 2, not HashML-DSA per
  composite-sigs §2.1) with the Label bytes as its native
  `mldsa_ctx`. The ECDSA half hashes `SHA-256(M')` for both
  ECDSA suites per composite-sigs §6 `ecdsa-with-SHA256`,
  regardless of the composite-layer PH. Signature
  serialisation is PQ-first concatenation per composite-sigs
  §4.3: `sig = sig_mldsa || sig_trad`, with `sig_trad` raw
  64-byte `R || S` for Ed25519 and DER-encoded
  `Ecdsa-Sig-Value` (RFC 3279 §2.2.3) for ECDSA-P256.
  Composite private keys carry the 32-byte ML-DSA seed only
  (composite-sigs §4.2); the expanded ML-DSA signing key is
  re-derived per sign via `keygenDerand` and never
  serialised, trading one ML-DSA keygen per sign for a clean
  seed-only sk encoding. All four suites are
  `StreamableSignatureSuite` and plug into `SignStream` /
  `VerifyStream` per composite-sigs §10.5 (external
  pre-hashing). `verifyPrehashed` always runs both
  sub-verifies regardless of intermediate outcomes (strictly
  stronger than composite-sigs §3.3's early-fail permission);
  ECDSA-half high-S signatures are normalised to low-S inside
  the composite verify path so spec-conformant high-S
  reference vectors accept without weakening the standalone
  `EcdsaP256Suite`. Per-suite `wasmModules` declares the
  required init modules: `['mldsa', 'sha3', 'curve25519',
  'sha2']` for the Ed25519 pair, `['mldsa', 'sha3', 'p256',
  'sha2']` for the ECDSA pair.

- **Envelope wire format gains a `payload_len: u32 BE`
  field.** The v3 attached envelope now carries an explicit
  4-byte payload length between the ctx and the payload bytes:
  `[suite_byte][ctx_len][ctx][payload_len][payload][sig]`.
  Variable-length signature schemes (the composite ECDSA
  hybrids at `0x22` / `0x23`, whose `Ecdsa-Sig-Value` DER
  encoding per RFC 3279 §2.2.3 varies 8-72 bytes) require
  length-aware framing for the parser to locate the sig
  bytes; the field is uniform across the catalog so every
  suite shares one parser. Sig fills the remaining envelope
  tail. Overhead is 4 bytes per signed blob, rounding error
  on PQ signature sizes. `Sign.peek` continues to return
  `{ suiteByte, ctx, payloadOffset, payloadLength, sigOffset
  }`; only the internal derivation changed. Every existing
  suite's KAT vector file was regenerated against the new
  wire. `signDetached` is unchanged: it returns the suite's
  natural sig bytes with no envelope framing.

- **`SignatureSuite.sigSize` renamed to `sigMaxSize`.**
  Semantics shifted from "exact bytes" to "upper bound
  bytes". For fixed-length suites (every existing pure /
  prehash / PQ-only hybrid / Ed25519 / ECDSA-P256 / composite
  ML-DSA-Ed25519 suite) the upper bound equals the actual
  size; for variable-length suites (composite ECDSA at
  `0x22` / `0x23`) the upper bound is the catalog-reserved
  maximum from composite-sigs Appendix A Table 4 (2492 bytes
  for `MlDsa44EcdsaP256Suite`, 3381 for
  `MlDsa65EcdsaP256Suite`). The field rename is mechanical
  across `src/ts/sign/types.ts`, every suite under
  `src/ts/sign/suites/`, every test asserting the field,
  and the docs catalog tables.

- **`USER_CTX_MAX` raised to 255 library-wide.**
  `src/ts/sign/ctx.ts` exports `USER_CTX_MAX = 255` to match
  FIPS 204 §3.6.1's native ctx cap and composite-sigs §3.2
  step 1's user_ctx cap. `buildEffectiveCtx` adds a second
  check that the combined `effective_ctx` fits the same
  255-byte FIPS 204 ctx parameter, so the per-call user_ctx
  ceiling on `buildEffectiveCtx`-using suites is `253 -
  len(ctxDomain)`, computed at call time. Composite suites
  skip `buildEffectiveCtx` and enforce the full 255-byte cap
  inline. Both check sites throw the same
  `SigningError('sig-ctx-too-long')` discriminator.

- **ECDSA-P256 primitive surface expansion.** Three new
  exports on the ECDSA module support the composite-sigs §4
  wire encodings:
  - `pointDecompress(pk33)`: free function that decompresses
    a 33-byte SEC 1 §2.3.3 compressed P-256 pk to the
    65-byte SEC 1 §2.3.4 uncompressed encoding `0x04 || X ||
    Y`. Solves `y² = x³ - 3x + b mod p` via the substrate's
    modular square root (p ≡ 3 mod 4 shortcut). Throws
    `SigningError('sig-malformed-input')` on bad-prefix
    bytes or off-curve x.
  - `EcdsaP256.keygenUncompressed(seed?)`: keygen variant
    that returns pk in the 65-byte uncompressed form
    directly. The standalone `EcdsaP256Suite` continues to
    use compressed pk; the uncompressed surface exists for
    callers (composite ML-DSA + ECDSA suites) whose wire
    format spec requires the SEC 1 §2.3.4 encoding.
  - `encodeEcPrivateKey(scalar)` / `decodeEcPrivateKey(der)`:
    RFC 5915 §3 DER `ECPrivateKey` codec for P-256. Encoder
    emits exactly 51 bytes (SEQUENCE 2 + version INTEGER 3 +
    `privateKey OCTET STRING` 34 + `parameters [0] EXPLICIT`
    12 with the secp256r1 named-curve OID
    `1.2.840.10045.3.1.7`). Decoder is strict DER per X.690
    §10: rejects long-form length under 128 bytes,
    non-minimal INTEGER on version, wrong OCTET STRING
    length, non-secp256r1 OID, trailing bytes, content
    extending past the outer SEQUENCE end. Accepts the
    optional `publicKey [1]` field and the parameters-omitted
    minimal form. These exports satisfy the composite-sigs
    §4.2 ECDSA private-key encoding requirement.

### Added (Phase 7 signature work, Merkle log + STH)

- **`merkle` module.** New TypeScript-only module under
  `src/ts/merkle/` that ships a C2SP-conformant transparency
  log substrate without adding a new WASM binary. The module
  is hash-agnostic at the algorithmic core (RFC 9162 §2.1.1 /
  §2.1.3 / §2.1.4 Merkle math) and bind-agnostic at the
  signature layer (any `SignatureSuite` registered in the
  c2sp.org/tlog-cosignature §Format algorithm-byte registry
  can cosign). Wire format follows c2sp.org/tlog-checkpoint
  §Note text for the body, c2sp.org/signed-note §Format for
  the envelope, and c2sp.org/tlog-cosignature §Format for the
  cosignature payload and signed-message construction.
  Subpath export: `leviathan-crypto/merkle`. No `/embedded`
  companion, no WASM blob.

- **`MerkleVerifier`.** Normie verify-only surface, the
  primary class most transparency-log consumers will reach
  for. Construct with `{ origin, pubkey, hashing: 'sha256' |
  'blake3', suite }`; the suite must be C2SP-registered
  (currently `Ed25519Suite` at algo byte 0x04 or
  `MlDsa44Suite` at algo byte 0x06). Three verify methods
  all return `boolean`: `verifyCheckpoint(envelopeBytes)`,
  `verifyInclusion({envelopeBytes, leafBytes, leafIndex,
  proof})`, `verifyConsistency({oldEnvelopeBytes,
  newEnvelopeBytes, proof})`. The verifier hashes raw leaf
  bytes itself via `hasher.hashLeaf(leafBytes)` before
  feeding `verifyInclusionProof`, which closes the "trust
  the leaf hash the caller passed us" gap. `verifyInclusion`
  and `verifyConsistency` both run `verifyCheckpoint` first
  and short-circuit to `false` on signature failure; the
  proof is never examined against an unverified root.
  Construction-time contract violations (empty / whitespaced
  / plus-containing origin, wrong-size pubkey, unsupported
  hashing, unsupported suite, uninitialised module) throw
  `MerkleLogError` with a stable discriminator.

- **`MerkleLog`.** Normie producer surface. Memory-backed
  via the existing `MemoryStorage`; suitable for in-process
  logs, fixtures, demo code, and small embedded uses.
  `MerkleLog.create({ origin, signingKey, pubkey, hashing?,
  suite? })` and the keypair-generating `MerkleLog.generate({
  origin, hashing?, suite? })` are async; `append`, `head`,
  `size`, `rootHash`, `inclusionProof`, `consistencyProof`,
  and `dispose` are synchronous per the merkle layer's locked
  sync invariant. Defaults resolve to `hashing: 'sha256'`
  (C2SP-interop) and `suite: MlDsa44Suite` (C2SP-recommended
  PQ default per c2sp.org/tlog-checkpoint). Unregistered
  suites raise `MerkleLogError('unsupported-suite')` before
  `SignedLog` is constructed, so the surfacing error class
  matches the normie surface rather than the lower-level
  `SigningError('sig-unsupported-suite')`.

- **`SignedLog<S extends SignatureSuite>`.** Danger-zone
  composition surface. Ties a `MerkleTree` (`Sha256Tree` or
  `Blake3Tree`), a registered cosignature `SignatureSuite`,
  and an origin string into one object. Dispatches the
  cosignature signed-message construction on the algorithm's
  `messageConstruction` field: `'cosig'` (Ed25519 + the
  `cosignature/v1` prefix per §"Ed25519 signed message") and
  `'cosigned-message'` (ML-DSA-44 + the TLS-Presentation
  `cosigned_message` struct per §"ML-DSA-44 signed message").
  `signCheckpoint({ timestamp? })` emits a signed-note
  envelope; `verifyCheckpoint(bytes)` returns boolean;
  `parseCheckpoint(bytes)` returns a structured
  `SignedTreeHead`; `dispose()` wipes the stored signing-key
  copy. Suite-rejection path throws
  `SigningError('sig-unsupported-suite')`.

- **`Sha256Tree`, `Blake3Tree`, `Sha256Hasher`,
  `Blake3Hasher`.** Two `MerkleTree` specialisations sharing
  one algorithmic core. The SHA-256 tree uses the RFC 9162
  §2.1.1 prefix-byte convention (`0x00` for leaves, `0x01`
  for internal nodes). The BLAKE3 tree uses BLAKE3's native
  flag-byte separation: leaves go through the chunk pipeline
  with `CHUNK_START` / `CHUNK_END` / `ROOT` flags;
  internal nodes use the §2.5 parent compress with the
  BLAKE3 IV as the starting CV, `modeFlags = 0`, and
  `isRoot = 0` at every level. The BLAKE3 path deliberately
  does NOT stack RFC 6962 prefix bytes on top of BLAKE3, as
  doing so would be redundant separation and would discard
  `compress4` parallelism at the internal-node layer.

- **Free-function proof verifiers and builders.**
  `verifyInclusionProof`, `verifyConsistencyProof`,
  `buildInclusionProof`, `buildConsistencyProof`. Each takes
  a `Hasher` argument and decides RFC 9162 §2.1.3 / §2.1.4
  in isolation; the builders take a `getNode(level, index)`
  callback so file and database backends can drive the same
  algorithm. Soft-fail conditions (wrong proof length, wrong
  sibling size, mismatched reconstruction) return `false`;
  caller-contract violations (out-of-range `leafIndex`,
  `treeSize < 1`, wrong-sized roots, `oldSize > newSize`)
  throw `RangeError`.

- **C2SP wire-format codec.** `serializeCheckpointBody` /
  `parseCheckpointBody` for c2sp.org/tlog-checkpoint §Note
  text; `emitSignedNote` / `parseSignedNote` for
  c2sp.org/signed-note §Format envelopes (parser is
  permissive on per-line malformations per the §Signatures
  "unknown signatures MUST be ignored" rule, strict on
  whole-envelope structure); `emitCosigSignaturePayload` /
  `parseCosigSignaturePayload` for the
  c2sp.org/tlog-cosignature §Format `timestamped_signature`
  struct; `buildCosigSignedMessage` and
  `buildCosignedMessage` for the Ed25519 and ML-DSA-44
  signed-message constructions; `deriveKeyId` for the
  4-byte SHA-256-derived key ID stamped on every signature
  line. The `ALGO_REGISTRY` const in `signed-note.ts` is the
  single source of truth for the `(formatEnum, algoByte,
  messageConstruction, signaturePayload, sigSize)` mapping;
  `lookupAlgoEntryByFormatEnum`, `lookupAlgoEntryByByte`,
  and `suiteFormatEnumToAlgoByte` expose it to consumers.

- **`MerkleStorage` and `MemoryStorage`.** Sync per-node
  persistence interface plus the in-process backend. Two-axis
  key (level, index); level 0 is the leaf row, level >= 1
  stores only perfect aligned subtree hashes. Partial
  right-edge subtree roots are recomputed on demand by the
  tree. File and database backends are documented extension
  surface; users implement `MerkleStorage` over their
  preferred persistence and feed it to `Sha256Tree` /
  `Blake3Tree`.

- **`MerkleLogError` and `MerkleCodecError`.** Two new
  error classes. `MerkleLogError` covers construction-time
  contract violations of the normie surface (`MerkleLog` /
  `MerkleVerifier`); documented discriminators
  `'origin-invalid'`, `'pubkey-size'`,
  `'unsupported-hashing'`, `'unsupported-suite'`,
  `'module-not-initialized'`. `MerkleCodecError` covers
  wire-format violations in the cosignature payload codec;
  documented discriminators `'timestamp-out-of-range'`,
  `'timestamp-exceeds-safe-integer'`,
  `'cosig-payload-length-mismatch'`,
  `'cosigner-name-length'`, `'log-origin-length'`,
  `'cosigned-message-state'`. Both extend `Error`; the
  normie verify methods on `MerkleVerifier` never throw on
  envelope or proof content (boolean-only), matching
  `SignatureSuite.verify`.

- **C2SP-interop notes.** The suite-selection constraint
  applies uniformly to the normie surface and the danger
  zone: only suites with a registered c2sp.org/tlog-cosignature
  §Format algorithm byte can produce or verify
  wire-format-conformant cosignature envelopes. The leviathan
  signature catalog contains many more suites
  (`EcdsaP256Suite`, prehash variants, ML-DSA-65/87, every
  SLH-DSA, every hybrid) but none of those have a registered
  byte yet; they cannot be passed to `MerkleLog`,
  `MerkleVerifier`, or `SignedLog`. The registry grows
  additively as C2SP registers more algorithm bytes; future
  additions land in `ALGO_REGISTRY` and unlock the
  corresponding suite for both surfaces in one edit.

### Changed (Phase 7)

- **BLAKE3 merkle substrate rename: `blake3-log.ts` →
  `blake3-tree.ts`.** Five repo-internal references updated
  per the Trillian-PR-2452-style layered split: the file is
  the tree layer; the log surface lives in `merkle-log.ts`
  with `signed-log.ts` underneath. No public-API symbol
  renamed; `Blake3Tree` / `Blake3Hasher` were always the
  public names.

### Migration (Phase 7)

None. Phase 7 is additive against the v2 baseline; v3.0.0
ships a superset of v2's public surface. The merkle module
is a new subpath and a new set of root-barrel exports, and
no existing surface changed shape. Consumers upgrading from
v2 see only the v3.0 wire-format break for `SerpentCipher`
documented earlier in this release; Phase 7 itself
introduces no breaking change.

## v2.1.0

### Added

- **Sparse Post-Quantum Ratchet (SPQR).** New module adding Double-Ratchet-style
  messaging primitives with ML-KEM post-quantum key encapsulation. Requires
  `init({ sha2 })` for the KDF-only layer; `init({ sha2, kyber, sha3 })` for
  the full KEM layer.
  - `ratchetInit(sharedSecret)` / `ratchetReady(state)`: initialise and probe
    symmetric ratchet state from a shared root secret.
  - `kemRatchetEncap(kem, rootKey, peerEk, context?)`: KEM ratchet step
    (encap side); returns `{ sendChainKey, recvChainKey, kemCt }`.
  - `kemRatchetDecap(kem, rootKey, dk, kemCt, ownEk, context?)`: KEM ratchet
    step (decap side); binds `(peerEk, kemCt, context)` into HKDF info for
    transcript integrity.
  - `KDFChain(chainKey)`: forward-secret per-message KDF chain. `step()`
    returns the next 32-byte message key and advances the chain;
    `stepWithCounter()` returns `{ key, counter }` atomically. `dispose()`
    wipes the chain key.
  - `SkippedKeyStore`: MKSKIPPED cache (DR spec §3.2/§3.5). `resolve(chain,
    counter)` returns a `ResolveHandle`: call `handle.commit()` on successful
    decrypt (wipes the key) or `handle.rollback()` on auth failure (preserves
    the key for a legitimate retry at the same counter). Split budgets:
    `maxCacheSize` (default 100) bounds memory; `maxSkipPerResolve` (default
    50) bounds per-message HKDF work. `advanceToBoundary(chain, pn)` for epoch
    transitions; `wipeAll()` on teardown.
  - `RatchetKeypair(kem)`: single-use ek/dk wrapper. `decap(kem, rootKey,
    kemCt)` decapsulates exactly once then wipes the dk. `dispose()` is
    idempotent.
  - `RatchetMessageHeader` interface: `{ epoch, counter, pn?, kemCt? }`.

- **Fortuna pluggable primitives.** `Fortuna` now accepts any compatible
  cipher generator and hash function via the new `Generator` and `HashFn`
  interfaces, rather than hardcoding Serpent-256 + SHA-256.
  - `SerpentGenerator` (`leviathan-crypto/serpent`) wraps Serpent-256 in
    counter mode, matching *Practical Cryptography* §9.4.
  - `ChaCha20Generator` (`leviathan-crypto/chacha20`) wraps the ChaCha20
    block function as a PRF with fixed zero nonce and 32-bit counter.
  - `SHA256Hash` (`leviathan-crypto/sha2`) and `SHA3_256Hash`
    (`leviathan-crypto/sha3`) are stateless hash primitives for the
    accumulator and reseed key derivation.
  - `Generator` and `HashFn` interfaces in `src/ts/types.ts`, also
    re-exported from the root barrel.
  - All four `(generator, hash)` combinations are exercised by KAT
    regression vectors in `test/vectors/fortuna_kat.ts`.
  - Tree-shaking: a chacha-only consumer no longer pulls Serpent's 123 KB
    WASM module just to use the CSPRNG. The bundle now reflects the
    primitive choice exactly.

### Breaking Changes

- **⚠ `OpenStream.seek(index)` rejects backward seeks.** When `index < this.counter`,
	`seek` now throws `RangeError` with `'forward-only'` in the
	message. Backward seek would re-use an already- consumed per-chunk counter
	nonce against a new ciphertext, permitting plaintext replay against a stale
	opener. Seek to the current counter is still a no-op. Construct a fresh
	`OpenStream` from the same preamble to restart from the beginning.

- **⚠ ML-KEM auto-validates keys on use.** `MlKemBase.encapsulate(ek)`,
	`encapsulateDerand(ek, m)`, and `decapsulate(dk, c)` now invoke the FIPS 203
	§7.2 / §7.3 validity checks before any cryptographic work. Invalid keys throw
	`RangeError` with messages `leviathan-crypto: encapsulation key failed FIPS 203
	§7.2 validity check` or `leviathan-crypto: decapsulation key failed FIPS 203
	§7.3 validity check`. In 1.x the public `checkEncapsulationKey` /
	`checkDecapsulationKey` probes existed as separate boolean gates that callers
	had to remember to call. Both probes remain available for pre-flight inspection
	without exception.

- **⚠ Strict single-use on `ChaCha20Poly1305.encrypt` / `XChaCha20Poly1305.encrypt`.**
  Any throw from `encrypt()` (including `RangeError` on key or nonce length)
  now terminates the instance. A retry on the same AEAD always raises the
  single-use guard (`encrypt() already called on this instance`), never a
  fresh length error. Always allocate a new AEAD per message.

- **⚠ `constantTimeEqual` requires WebAssembly SIMD.** The JS
  XOR-accumulate fallback is removed. Runtimes without SIMD support
  throw `Error: leviathan-crypto: constantTimeEqual requires
  WebAssembly SIMD, this runtime does not support it` at first
  call, matching the existing preflight on `serpentInit`,
  `chacha20Init`, and `kyberInit`. The fallback was previously
  documented as "best-effort constant-time, not a hardware-level
  guarantee"; the library's overall posture is that SIMD is a
  baseline requirement, and `constantTimeEqual` should not silently
  degrade to a path whose constant-time properties depend on
  V8/SpiderMonkey JIT decisions. Impact scope: consumers who use
  `init({ sha2: ... })` or `init({ sha3: ... })` only (no serpent,
  chacha20, or kyber) AND call `constantTimeEqual` directly AND run
  on a non-SIMD runtime. All three conditions together. Consumers
  in this narrow band must either pin to 2.1.x or provide their own
  CT implementation.

- **⚠ `SealStream` / `OpenStream` add a `'failed'` terminal state for
  crypto-path throws.** Auth failures, WASM errors, and cipher exceptions
  from `push()`, `pull()`, or `finalize()` wipe the derived keys and
  transition the stream to state `'failed'`. Subsequent operations (including
  `OpenStream.seek`) throw with `'failed'` in the message instead of
  `'finalized'`. `dispose()` on a failed instance is a no-op. Argument-
  validation errors on `SealStream` (chunk larger than `chunkSize`) throw
  `RangeError` without mutating state or wiping keys. stream stays
  `'ready'` and the caller can retry with a corrected chunk. `OpenStream`
  does not make this distinction: wire-format errors on input ciphertext
  are terminal to avoid exposing error-type oracles on attacker-controlled
  streams.

- **`OpenStream.seek(index)` validates `index` fully before mutating
  `counter`.** Indices above `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER` throw `RangeError`
  at the seek site; previously they passed `Number.isInteger` and were
  stored, then failed on the next `pull()`/`finalize()` through
  `makeCounterNonce`, which ran inside the crypto-path try/catch and
  tripped the `'failed'` key-wiping cleanup. Backward seeks and
  non-integer/negative inputs were already validated; this closes the
  remaining gap so any seek argument error leaves the stream usable.

- **⚠ `hexToBytes` throws `RangeError` on non-hex characters.** Previously,
  `parseInt('0g', 16)` returned `0` (not `NaN`) because it stops at the first
  invalid character, and the resulting bytes were silently wrong. A leading
  regex test now rejects any input containing characters outside
  `[0-9a-fA-F]`. Odd-length input already threw and that behaviour is preserved.

- **⚠ `base64ToBytes` throws `RangeError` on invalid input.** Previously
  returned `undefined` for illegal charsets or `rem=1` length. The new
  behaviour matches the throw-don't-return-null convention used everywhere
  else in the library (AEAD `decrypt`, key validation, etc). Return type is
  now `Uint8Array`, not `Uint8Array | undefined`. Callers doing
  `if (bytes) { ... }` should drop the check and let throws propagate.

- **⚠ `Fortuna.create()` requires explicit `generator` and `hash`.** No
  defaults. Both must be passed:

  ```typescript
  // 2.0-2.1:
  Fortuna.create()
  Fortuna.create({ msPerReseed: 200 })

  // 2.1.0:
  import { SerpentGenerator } from 'leviathan-crypto/serpent'
  import { SHA256Hash } from 'leviathan-crypto/sha2'

  Fortuna.create({ generator: SerpentGenerator, hash: SHA256Hash })
  Fortuna.create({ generator: SerpentGenerator, hash: SHA256Hash, msPerReseed: 200 })
  ```

  Migration for the legacy implicit pair: add
  `{ generator: SerpentGenerator, hash: SHA256Hash }` to every existing
  `Fortuna.create(...)` call. The `msPerReseed` and `entropy` options are
  unchanged. `Fortuna.create()` with no arguments now throws `TypeError`,
  and `Fortuna.create({})` throws the same.

  `Fortuna.create()` also asserts
  `hash.outputSize === generator.keySize` and throws `RangeError` if you
  pair primitives of different sizes. All four shipped combinations
  satisfy this constraint (every shipped primitive uses 32-byte keys and
  32-byte digests).

  **Migration table for Fortuna:**

  | 2.0-2.1                              | 2.1.0                                                                                |
  | ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
  | `Fortuna.create()`                   | `Fortuna.create({ generator: SerpentGenerator, hash: SHA256Hash })`                  |
  | `Fortuna.create({ msPerReseed: N })` | `Fortuna.create({ generator: SerpentGenerator, hash: SHA256Hash, msPerReseed: N })`  |
  | `Fortuna.create({ entropy })`        | `Fortuna.create({ generator: SerpentGenerator, hash: SHA256Hash, entropy })`         |

  To pick a different cipher or hash, substitute `ChaCha20Generator` or
  `SHA3_256Hash`. All four combinations are valid.

### Security

- **Post-dispose method-call guard on stateful classes.** `SHAKE128`, `SHAKE256`,
  `ChaCha20`, `SerpentCtr`, and `SerpentCbc` now throw
  `Error: <ClassName>: instance has been disposed` if any instance method is
  invoked after `dispose()`. Previously, a disposed instance's methods would
  still run against the shared WASM module (which by then might belong to a
  different class), silently clobbering the live instance's state. Closes
  the remaining shared-WASM-clobber sub-cases the construction-time
  exclusivity guard does not reach.

- **Kyber operations now hold the `sha3` exclusivity guard.**
  `MlKemBase.keygenDerand`, `encapsulateDerand`, `decapsulate`,
  `checkEncapsulationKey`, and `checkDecapsulationKey` now call
  `_assertNotOwned('sha3')` and `_assertNotOwned('kyber')` at entry. Without
  this, a live `SHAKE128` / `SHAKE256` instance plus any kyber op would
  silently re-initialize the sha3 sponge mid-stream.

- **Fortuna wipe-before-reassign discipline across all state transitions.**
  `pseudoRandomData`, `reseed`, `addRandomEvent`, and the pool-reset branch
  inside `get()` now zero the prior `Uint8Array` before dropping its
  reference. Without this, the old generator key and entropy-pool chain
  values were reachable through lingering references to the replaced
  buffers. Forward secrecy of the CSPRNG depends on the prior state being
  unrecoverable.

- **`Fortuna.stop()` is now a complete teardown.** It wipes `genKey`,
  `genCnt`, and every one of the 32 pool-hash chain values, and disposes
  the inner `Serpent` and `SHA256` instances so their WASM exclusivity
  tokens are released and their linear-memory buffers are zeroed.
  Previously `stop()` left the pool-hash values, the Serpent subkey
  schedule, and the SHA-256 intermediate state in memory.

- **`SerpentCipher.sealChunk` / `openChunk` now wipe on any throw.** The
  HMAC, CBC, intermediate IV, and tag input buffers are disposed /
  zeroed in a `finally` block so an unexpected throw mid-chunk does not
  leak key material through lingering references. The auth-failure
  explicit-wipe path remains in place as defense in depth.

- **`aeadDecrypt` auth-failure wipes the ChaCha keystream block buffer
  and the Poly1305 one-time subkey.** The 64-byte `CHACHA_BLOCK_BUFFER`
  holds the last-generated Poly1305 one-time-key block; on auth failure
  it is now zeroed alongside the `CHUNK_CT` buffer. `chachaGenPolyKey`
  additionally copies that block's first 32 bytes to `POLY_KEY_BUFFER`
  (`POLY_KEY_OFFSET = 131248`) as the Poly1305 key for this (key, nonce) pair.
  This is outside the 48..112 `CHACHA_BLOCK` range, so the auth-fail
  branch now also zeroes `POLY_KEY_BUFFER[0..32]`. Under strict
  single-use the instance is locked after the throw, so this wipe
  closes the window before the next chacha op would overwrite the
  subkey organically.

- **`kemDecapsulate` zeroes its scratch slots.** The CPA secret key (`skCpa`),
  message representative (`m'`), shared-secret candidates, noise polyvecs,
  uncompressed `u`, and the PRF output block are all wiped before returning.
  `skCpa` is the highest-severity residual, exposure compromises every
  ciphertext under the corresponding `ek`. No secret-derived bytes persist in
  kyber linear memory across a decapsulate call.

- **`kemEncapsulateDerand` zeroes its scratch slots.** The randomness `m`,
  noise polyvecs, uncompressed intermediate polynomials, and PRF output block
  are wiped before returning. `m` is the highest-severity residual, it plus
  the public `ek` reproduces the shared secret. Public output (`CT_OFFSET`,
  `PK_OFFSET`) is intentionally preserved.

- **`kemKeypairDerand` zeroes its scratch slots.** The CPA secret key
  (`skCpa`), secret/error polyvecs, and PRF output block are wiped before
  returning the keypair. Previously `skCpa` persisted for the entire session
  lifetime under the common "keygen once, encap many" pattern, same severity
  class as the decap residual. Public matrix and `t̂` slots are intentionally
  preserved.

- **Kyber public ops now zero sha3 scratch before returning.**
  `kemKeypairDerand`, `kemEncapsulateDerand`, `kemDecapsulate`, and
  `checkDecapsulationKey` each call `sx.wipeBuffers()` as the final step
  on every path that executed sha3 work. This runs inside the
  `_assertNotOwned('sha3')` window the kyber op holds for its duration,
  so no live `SHAKE128` / `SHAKE256` instance can have its state
  clobbered by the wipe, that was the reason `MlKemBase.dispose()`
  stopped wiping sha3 earlier in this release cycle. The invariant that
  no secret-derived sha3 residue persists across a kyber op boundary
  previously relied on "the last sha3 call in every kyber path happens
  to be keyed on public material" (SHAKE128 of public ρ for the
  A-matrix expansion; SHA3-256 of public ek in the dk-assembly step of
  keygen), a structural property maintained by manual discipline. That
  invariant is now enforced mechanically: every public kyber op leaves
  sha3 STATE, INPUT, and OUT regions zero regardless of call ordering.
  Future refactors that reorder sha3 calls within a kyber op cannot
  silently introduce residue.

- **`MlKemBase.dispose()` no longer wipes sha3 buffers.** The previous
  `this.sx.wipeBuffers()` call at dispose time zeroed shared sha3 linear
  memory and clobbered any live `SHAKE128` / `SHAKE256` sponge held by
  another caller. The wipe is unnecessary: every public kyber op now
  zeros sha3 scratch before returning (see above), so sha3 scratch
  carries no residue across a kyber op boundary. `MlKemBase.dispose()`
  cleans only the kyber module, which it does own.

  Across all three public KEM operations (keygen, encapsulate,
  decapsulate), no kyber secret or secret-derived data persists in WASM
  linear memory between ops. Lifecycle-level wipe via `MlKem.dispose()`
  → `wipeBuffers()` continues to cover the entire layout.

- **`_resetForTesting` no longer reaches the public package surface.**
	The function is tagged `@internal` in `init.ts` and stripped from
	`dist/init.d.ts` by `stripInternal: true`. The root barrel
	`src/ts/index.ts` previously re-exported it without JSDoc, which
	carries no `@internal` tag and bypasses `stripInternal`, so the
	symbol leaked into `dist/index.d.ts` and `dist/index.js` anyway. A
	consumer could import it from the public package and zero the
	exclusivity-owners registry while a live stateful instance still
	held its token, re-enabling the shared-WASM-state clobber the
	exclusivity guard exists to prevent. The re-export is removed. The
	regression guard now scans both `dist/init.d.ts` and
	`dist/index.d.ts` for every `@internal`-tagged symbol in `init.ts`.
	The public readiness probes (`_sha2Ready`, `_sha3Ready`,
	`_serpentReady`, `_chachaReady`, `_kyberReady`) are intentional
	underscore-prefixed exports and are unaffected.

- **SHA-2 atomic `dispose()` asserts non-ownership before wiping.**
	`SHA256`, `SHA512`, `SHA384`, `HMAC_SHA256`, `HMAC_SHA512`, and
	`HMAC_SHA384` now call `_assertNotOwned('sha2')` as the first
	statement of `dispose()`, matching the pattern already used by the
	SHA-3, ChaCha20, and Serpent atomics. No stateful SHA-2 class
	currently ships, so the gap was latent; closing it now prevents a
	future stateful SHA-2 user (streaming HMAC, stateful KDF) from
	having its key schedule silently clobbered by an unrelated atomic's
	dispose.

- **Fully branch-free `pkcs7Strip`.** The per-iteration pad-region
	mask previously used a JS ternary on a value derived from the
	trailing plaintext byte, the exact surface the Vaudenay-2002
	padding oracle manipulates. The clamp on that value used
	`Math.min(Math.max(...))`, which has no constant-time contract
	under JS engines. The mask is now computed via arithmetic-shift on
	a signed int32 and the clamp is gone; every operation on the
	secret byte is a pure bit-twiddle with no spec-level branch. The
	raw `SerpentCbc({ dangerUnauthenticated: true })` surface now
	literally matches the branch-free claim on the PKCS7 step. The
	recommended `SerpentCipher` path was not affected even before this
	change, HMAC-verify-then-decrypt ordering makes the PKCS7 step
	unreachable to an attacker who cannot forge a tag.

- **Pool worker wipe waits for acknowledgement before termination.**
	`SealStreamPool._killAll` previously posted `{type: 'wipe'}` to
	each worker and immediately called `worker.terminate()`.
	`terminate()` aborts synchronously and drops any queued messages
	per WHATWG, so the worker-held 32-byte ChaCha20 subkey (or 96-byte
	Serpent derived-keys buffer) and the worker's WASM linear memory
	were not guaranteed to be zeroed before the worker died. Workers
	now reply with `{type: 'wiped'}` after completing the wipe, and
	the main thread waits up to 100 ms per worker before falling
	through to `terminate()`. Main-thread `_masterKey` and derived-key
	wipes run synchronously as before. `destroy()` remains synchronous
	from the caller's perspective, the pool is observably dead the
	moment it returns; worker teardown is bounded-async in the
	background.

- **Stateful `dispose()` bodies use `try`/`finally` around
	`wipeBuffers()`.** `SerpentCtr.dispose()`, `SerpentCbc.dispose()`,
	`ChaCha20.dispose()`, `SHAKE128.dispose()`, and
	`SHAKE256.dispose()` previously released their module's
	exclusivity token only on the happy path; a throw out of
	`wipeBuffers()` stranded the token and wedged the module for the
	rest of the process. `memory.fill` does not throw on any shipping
	JS runtime today, so this was theoretical. The `try`/`finally`
	makes the "dispose always releases" invariant unconditional.

- **Fortuna pool-selection now matches *Practical Cryptography* §9.5.5.**
	Prior versions used a bit-test (`reseedCnt & (1 << i)`) where the spec
	requires a divisibility test (`r % (1 << i) === 0`, equivalently
	`r & ((1 << i) - 1) === 0`). The two coincide only at `r = 1`. From
	`r = 2` onward they diverge: under the bit-test, pool 0 was drained on
	roughly half of all reseeds instead of every reseed, and the wide-mix
	recovery property at `r = 2^i` (where the spec uses pools 0..i
	together) never happened. The CSPRNG output remained pseudorandom
	because the new key still derives via SHA-256-hash of the prior key
	concatenated with whatever pool data was selected; the formal recovery
	argument from the original paper is what the bug weakened. Schedule
	is now spec-correct. Regression test:
	`test/unit/fortuna/spec-conformance.test.ts`.

- **Fortuna fails loudly when no entropy source is available.**
	Previously `Fortuna.create()` could resolve in environments lacking
	both `crypto.getRandomValues` and `node:crypto` and silently produce
	deterministic output keyed by all zeros. `create()` now asserts that
	pool 0 received at least 64 bits of entropy from the OS source during
	initialization and throws
	`'leviathan-crypto: Fortuna initialization could not gather sufficient entropy. No working crypto.getRandomValues or node:crypto in this environment.'`
	otherwise. Reachable only in non-standard JavaScript runtimes (modern
	browsers and Node always expose at least one source); the
	silent-failure path is closed. Regression test in
	`test/unit/fortuna/pluggable-primitives.test.ts`.

- **`cbd2` (FIPS 203 §4.2.2 Algorithm 7) regression-pinned at the byte
	level.** Three KATs in `test/unit/kyber/poly_arithmetic.test.ts`
	Gate 5 lock down cbd2's exact spec contract: input independence
	(coefficients 0..255 are uniquely determined by buffer bytes 0..127
	only, never bytes 128..255), destination footprint (no write past
	the 512-byte output polynomial, verified by 0xA5 sentinel-fill on
	the adjacent poly slot), and exact coefficient agreement with an
	inline FIPS 203 Algorithm 7 reference over 100 random inputs. The
	pre-existing range invariant (`coeff ∈ [−2, 2]`) holds structurally
	regardless of input length or iteration count, so it pins the
	output range but not the byte budget or write footprint; the new
	tests close that gap.

### Changed

- **`loader.ts` accepts any `PromiseLike<WasmSource>`.** The structural
  thenable check now resolves the promise first and recursively re-dispatches
  by the runtime type of the resolved value (so `Promise<ArrayBuffer>`,
  `Promise<Uint8Array>`, and `Promise<string>` (gzip+base64 blob) work
  alongside the already-supported `Promise<Response>`. Previously these
  silently fell into `WebAssembly.compileStreaming`, which only accepts
  `Response` / `Promise<Response>`, and produced an opaque browser-layer error.
  Recursion is capped at depth 3. Deeper nesting throws
  `TypeError: thenable nesting too deep (max 3)`. The public type
  `WasmSource` widens its last branch from `Promise<Response>` to
  `PromiseLike<WasmSource>`). Consumers using `Promise<Response>` are unaffected.

- **`SerpentCipher` and the serpent pool worker share one primitive
  implementation.** HMAC-SHA256, Serpent-CBC chunk encrypt/decrypt, and
  PKCS7 pad/strip are extracted into `src/ts/serpent/shared-ops.ts` as pure
  functions taking sha2/serpent WASM exports as parameters. Both
  `cipher-suite.ts` (main thread) and `pool-worker.ts` call the same code.
  Three knock-on effects: (a) the pool worker now uses
  `cbcDecryptChunk_simd`, matching main-thread `SerpentCbc.decrypt` instead
  of the scalar fallback. Multi-chunk pool decrypts pick up the SIMD
  speedup. (b) The pool worker's previously distinguishable PKCS7 error
  messages (`empty ciphertext`, `invalid PKCS7 padding`) are gone; the
  Vaudenay 2002 oracle closure in `shared-ops.pkcs7Strip` now applies on
  both sides. (c) Main-thread `sealChunk`/`openChunk` drop the per-chunk
  `new HMAC_SHA256()` / `new SerpentCbc()` construction; the exclusivity
  guard those constructors contributed is now asserted explicitly via
  `_assertNotOwned('serpent')` + `_assertNotOwned('sha2')`. Not
  user-visible; flagged as a build-touching change for downstream
  worker-bundle rebuilds.

- **`randomBytes` throws a branded error on runtimes without Web
	Crypto.** `randomBytes(n)` previously let a missing
	`globalThis.crypto.getRandomValues` surface as a plain
	`ReferenceError: crypto is not defined` with no library
	attribution. The function now guards explicitly and throws
	`Error('leviathan-crypto: crypto.getRandomValues is required,
	this runtime does not expose the Web Crypto API')`, matching the
	"fail loudly with attribution" convention documented in
	`AGENTS.md` §Memory and Security and the pattern already used by
	`Fortuna.collectorCryptoRandom`.

- **Pool worker spawn mechanism.** Pool workers are now bundled into
  self-contained IIFE source strings at lib build time
  (`scripts/embed-workers.ts`) and spawned via classic blob URLs from
  inside `cipher-suite.ts`. This replaces the previous
  `new Worker(new URL('./pool-worker.js', import.meta.url), { type: 'module' })`
  pattern that triggered eager worker-chunk emission in Vite's transform
  hook (shipping orphan chunks for unused cipher suites) and that failed
  under `file://` in Chromium with module-worker cross-origin checks. The
  shipping `dist/<cipher>/pool-worker.js` files remain in the package as
  build inputs but are no longer the runtime spawn entries. Strict-CSP
  consumers (`worker-src 'self'`, no `blob:`) can spread-override
  `createPoolWorker` on the cipher object to plug in a URL-based factory;
  see `docs/ciphersuite.md`.

- **Build pipeline.** Added `build:embed-workers` step (between
  `build:embed` and `build:ts`) and `esbuild` as a devDependency. The new
  step bundles each pool worker into an IIFE for the change described
  above. The unit-test workflows under `.github/workflows/` and the
  `test` script in `package.json` were updated to invoke the new step
  before vitest.

### Documentation

- **`docs/aead.md`: documents `chunkSize` header as a maximum, not an
  actual size.** For `Seal.encrypt` (single-chunk), the header always
  declares `max(plaintext.length, CHUNK_MIN)`. A zero-byte seal still
  declares `chunkSize = CHUNK_MIN = 1024`. This is length-hiding, not a
  size declaration.

- **`docs/architecture.md`: "Five Independent WASM Modules" → "Six".** Adds
  a row for the `ct` utility module (SIMD constant-time compare). `ct` is
  internal and not part of the public `Module` union.

- **`docs/chacha20.md`: documents `ChaCha20.beginEncrypt` counter=1
  convention.** `beginEncrypt()` starts the keystream at block counter 1
  per RFC 8439 §2.6 (block 0 is reserved for Poly1305 key generation).
  Users diffing against RFC 8439 §2.4.2 (counter=0) expected a different
  output; now called out.

- **`docs/aead.md`: documents `SealStreamPool` lifecycle.** `seal()` leaves
  the master key and derived keys resident until `destroy()`. `open()`
  remains valid after a successful `seal()`, which can be surprising given
  the "sealed" label. On any throw the pool enters `dead` state with all
  keys wiped.

- **`docs/sha3_audit.md`: adds a note on SHAKE dispose semantics.** The
  original "wipe semantics correct" analysis stands; the exclusivity
  token held by `SHAKE128` / `SHAKE256` and the post-dispose method-call
  throws are additional guarantees layered on top, not a contradiction.

- **`src/asm/kyber/params.ts`: corrected the QINV docstring.** The comment
  claimed `q * QINV ≡ -1 mod 2^16` and `(3329 * -3327) & 0xFFFF == 0xFFFF`;
  the pq-crystals Montgomery convention is `q * QINV ≡ 1 mod 2^16` and the
  masked product is `0x0001`. Constant value `QINV = -3327` is unchanged
  (it was correct; only the docstring was wrong).

- **`docs/aead.md` documents the `SealStreamPool.open()` unframed
	chunk-shape requirement.** `pool.open()` on unframed ciphertext
	assumes every non-final chunk is exactly `chunkSize` plaintext
	bytes. A blob produced by `SealStream.push()` with sub-full-size
	chunks decrypts correctly through `OpenStream` but fails
	authentication through `pool.open()` because the pool's split
	boundary does not match the producer's. `framed: true` on both
	sides makes the interop work regardless of per-chunk size. The
	asymmetry is now called out explicitly in the pool section.

- **`docs/kyber.md` frames `decapsulate`'s §7.3 pre-check as input
	validation, not FO uniformity.** The §7.3 validity check on `dk`
	throws `RangeError` on malformed key material. The FO transform
	returns a pseudorandom shared secret on tampered or otherwise
	invalid ciphertext. These two error behaviors are not uniform and
	are not intended to be: FIPS 203 positions §7.3 as input
	validation on key storage, and ML-KEM's threat model assumes `dk`
	is recipient-controlled local storage. Callers whose protocols
	expose `dk` to adversarial supply can pre-probe via
	`checkDecapsulationKey(dk)` to bring §7.3 failure into the same
	branch as other input-validation errors. No runtime change; no
	strict-mode flag shipped in this release.

- **`docs/ratchet.md` documents the commit-vs-rollback timing
	asymmetry on `SkippedKeyStore`.** `commit` zeroes a 32-byte key
	buffer; `rollback` may evict the oldest cached entry and always
	inserts into the skipped-key map. The asymmetry is observable to
	a network-layer attacker timing the receiver's per-message
	processing, but only under narrow conditions. Specifically,
	when a tampered ciphertext arrives at a given counter before the
	legitimate message with the same counter. What the attacker
	learns is whether the legitimate message has already been
	processed by the receiver, not any key or plaintext bit. The
	information overlaps with what a transport-layer observer
	already has via message-delivery visibility. The library ships
	no runtime padding in this release; protocols whose threat
	model includes this leak can pad at their own layer.

- **`docs/init.md` `WasmSource` type alias matches the actual type.**
	Previously documented as `... | Response | Promise<Response>`;
	the actual type in `src/ts/wasm-source.ts` ends with
	`| PromiseLike<WasmSource>` and the loader resolves nested
	thenables recursively up to depth 3 (as already documented in
	`docs/loader.md`). The alias and one explanatory sentence in
	`init.md` are updated to agree.

- **`SECURITY.md` wording: Poly1305 tag compare.** The sentence
	describing where the Poly1305 tag is compared previously placed
	the compare "inside the WASM `aeadDecrypt` call", implying a
	WASM-side check analogous to Kyber's in-WASM `ct_verify`. The
	compare actually happens in TypeScript via `constantTimeEqual`,
	which runs entirely inside the dedicated WASM SIMD constant-time
	module (v128 XOR-accumulate with branch-free reduction). This
	gates the call into the chacha20 WASM decrypt path. The wording
	now reflects the actual architecture. The ordering property
	(authentication before any plaintext production) is unchanged.

- **`docs/stream_audit.md` error-bucket enumeration matches the
	code.** The audit document previously listed three error-type
	buckets surfaceable from `OpenStream.pull` on adversarial input;
	the code actually surfaces six (state-machine error, framed
	chunk too short, framed chunk length mismatch, chunk too short
	to contain the tag, chunk exceeds max wire size,
	`AuthenticationError`). All six are now enumerated with the
	accompanying argument that none constitutes a cryptographic
	oracle: every distinguishable bucket depends only on input
	sizes the attacker chose, not on secret key bits, plaintext
	bytes, or tag-compare internals.

- **`docs/fortuna.md` rewritten** for the pluggable-primitives API. New
	sections cover the `(Generator, HashFn)` matrix, the spec deviations
	relative to *Practical Cryptography* (2003) §9.4 and §9.5, and updated
	coexistence rules covering both Serpent and ChaCha20 stateful cipher
	classes.

- **`docs/types.md`** documents the new `Generator` and `HashFn`
	interfaces.

- **`docs/architecture.md`, `docs/init.md`, `docs/exports.md`,
	`docs/examples.md`, `docs/CLAUDE_consumer.md`, `docs/test-suite.md`,
	`test/vectors/README.md`** updated to reflect the API change.

---

## v2.0.1

- Released: 2026-04-10

### Security

- **Silent data corruption in SerpentCipher pool.** `SealStreamPool` with
  `SerpentCipher` and `chunkSize: 65536` silently produced corrupt plaintext
  on decrypt for inputs >= 65536 bytes. The Serpent WASM CBC chunk buffer was
  sized at 65536 bytes, but PKCS7 on a full 65536-byte chunk always appends a
  full 16-byte padding block, producing a 65552-byte write. The 16-byte
  overflow clobbered adjacent WASM memory. Auth passed, output was wrong,
  and no error was raised. Fixed by expanding the WASM chunk buffers and all
  downstream offsets to accommodate the PKCS7 maximum.

### Changed

- **`CipherSuite` interface adds `wasmChunkSize`.** Replaces a throwaway WASM
  probe instantiation in `SealStreamPool.create()` with a static field.
  `SerpentCipher`: 65552. `XChaCha20Cipher`: 65536. `KyberSuite` forwards
  from its inner cipher.

- **`SealStreamPool.create()` validates padded chunk size statically.** For
  padded ciphers, pool creation now checks `paddedFull <= cipher.wasmChunkSize`
  at startup and throws a `RangeError` with the actual values if the check
  fails. The old probe-based approach is removed.

- **`cbcEncryptChunk` and `cbcDecryptChunk` return codes checked.** Both pool
  worker and `SerpentCbc` now inspect the WASM return value and throw a
  `RangeError` on rejection instead of silently reading from a potentially
  corrupt buffer region.

### Test Suite

- 582 unit tests (Vitest), 189 e2e tests (Playwright × 3 browsers), 771 total.
- New test files: `serpent_large_pool.spec.ts` (3 × 3 browsers).
  Covers `chunkSize: 65536` at 256 KB (4 full chunks), 5 MB (hash comparison),
  and the specific regression: full chunks must not decrypt to zeros.

---

## v2.0.0

- Released: 2026-04-10

### Breaking Changes

- **⚠ Streaming layer replaced.** `SerpentStreamSealer`, `SerpentStreamOpener`,
  `XChaCha20StreamSealer`, and `XChaCha20StreamOpener` are removed. Replaced by
  cipher-agnostic `SealStream`, `OpenStream`, and `SealStreamPool` which take a
  `CipherSuite` interface. The new wire format is incompatible with v1 streams.

- **⚠ New 20-byte header wire format.**
  Byte 0: compound enum (bit 7 = framed flag, bits 0-6 = cipher format enum).
  Bytes 1-16: nonce. Bytes 17-19: u24 big-endian chunk size.
  Per-chunk: 12-byte counter nonce (11-byte BE counter + 1-byte TAG_DATA/TAG_FINAL).
  STREAM construction per Rogaway OAE.

- **⚠ init() API redesigned.** `init(modules, mode, opts)` → `init(sources)` where
  `sources` is `Partial<Record<Module, WasmSource>>`. The loading strategy is
  inferred from the source type (no mode string). Accepts 7 source types:
  embedded string, URL, ArrayBuffer, Uint8Array, WebAssembly.Module, Response,
  or Promise\<Response\>.

- **⚠ SIMD is required for serpent and chacha20.** `init()` and `initModule()`
  perform a SIMD preflight check and throw a clear error on non-SIMD runtimes.
  The three `hasSIMD()` dispatch ternaries are removed. Serpent and chacha20
  always use their SIMD code paths. sha2 and sha3 modules are unaffected.

- **⚠ `hasSIMD()` is now a public utility, not an internal dispatch mechanism.**
  Exported from the barrel for consumers who want to feature-detect before
  calling init().

### Security

- **WASM SIMD `constantTimeEqual`.** Tag comparison is now performed by a
  dedicated WASM SIMD module (v128 XOR + `any_true`), eliminating JIT
  short-circuiting and speculative optimization as theoretical side-channel
  vectors. Lazy-initialized on first call; falls back to JS XOR-accumulate
  on runtimes without SIMD (sha2/sha3-only consumers). Max 32768 bytes per
  side (enforced on both code paths). WASM memory wiped after every comparison.

- **aeadDecrypt wipes full chunk buffer on auth failure.** Previously only
  wiped `ciphertext.length` bytes; now wipes the full `maxChunk` region.

- **SerpentSeal.decrypt wipes expectedTag.** HMAC output (derived from macKey)
  is zeroed via `try/finally` on both success and failure paths, consistent
  with SerpentCipher.openChunk.

- **SerpentCipher.openChunk and SerpentSeal.decrypt wipe WASM buffers
  on auth failure** via `getInstance('serpent').exports.wipeBuffers()`.

- **TransformStream key wipe on error.** Both `SealStream.toTransformStream()`
  and `OpenStream.toTransformStream()` wrap transform/flush in `try/catch` and
  call `dispose()` before rethrowing. Previously, a cipher error in the stream
  pipeline would leave derived keys in memory.

- **OpenStream enforces max wire chunk size.** Computed from `chunkSize` +
  padding + tag. Rejects oversized ciphertext in both `pull()` and `finalize()`.

- **Pool workers transfer ArrayBuffer ownership in both directions.** Job
  dispatch transfers `data` (and `counterNonce` where applicable); result
  handoff transfers the result buffer. Prevents redundant plaintext/ciphertext
  copies for large payloads.

### Added

- **SealStream / OpenStream**: Cipher-agnostic chunked streaming AEAD.
  HKDF key derivation at construction. Counter nonces with final-flag
  domain separation. Seekable via `seek(index)`. Framed mode for network
  transports. `toTransformStream()` for Web Streams API integration.

- **SealStreamPool**: Parallel batch AEAD via Web Workers. Round-robin
  chunk dispatch across N workers. Single-use seal guard (nonce reuse
  prevention). Any auth error kills all workers and wipes keys (no retry).

- **CipherSuite interface**: Protocol for cipher-agnostic streaming.
  `deriveKeys`, `sealChunk`, `openChunk`, `wipeKeys`, `createPoolWorker`.
  Shipped implementations: `XChaCha20Cipher` (format 0x01) and
  `SerpentCipher` (format 0x02).

- **ML-KEM (FIPS 203)**: Post-quantum key encapsulation mechanism.
  `MlKem512`, `MlKem768`, `MlKem1024` classes implementing the full
  Fujisaki-Okamoto KEM transform. SIMD-enabled WASM module (`kyber.wasm`)
  requiring WebAssembly SIMD support, with NTT, Montgomery/Barrett reduction,
  CBD sampling, division-free compression. All three parameter sets validated against 240 NIST ACVP
  vectors (75 keygen, 75 encap, 30 decap with implicit rejection,
  60 key validity checks). Constant-time decapsulation path via
  dedicated WASM `ct_verify`/`ct_cmov`. Requires `sha3` module for
  Keccak sponge operations (SHAKE128/256, SHA3-256/512).

- **Keccak alias**: `'keccak'` module name resolves to `sha3` WASM
  binary. `keccakInit()`, `leviathan-crypto/keccak` and
  `leviathan-crypto/keccak/embedded` subpath exports.

- **AuthenticationError**: Dedicated error class with `this.name` set.
  Replaces generic `Error('authentication failed')` throughout.

- **writeHeader / readHeader / makeCounterNonce**: Header codec with full
  input validation (formatEnum range, nonce length, chunkSize u24 bounds,
  finalFlag tag whitelist, counter safe integer bounds).

### Changed

- **init() validates source values.** `{ sha2: undefined as any }` now
  throws a module-scoped TypeError instead of falling through to a
  generic loader error.

- **init() uses `Object.hasOwn`** for dispatcher key validation instead
  of `in` operator (prevents prototype-chain bypass).

- **CT_WASM buffer isolation.** `.buffer.slice(byteOffset, byteOffset + byteLength)`
  ensures correct bytes if a bundler merges the backing ArrayBuffer.

- **Thenable duck-typing in loader.** `instanceof Promise` replaced with
  `.then` property check in both `compileWasm` and `loadWasm` for
  cross-realm compatibility.

### Internal

- **WASM CT module.** `src/asm/ct/index.ts` is ~175 bytes compiled,
  SIMD-only, `--importMemory`, 1 page, no source map. Embedded as raw
  byte array literal in `src/ts/ct-wasm.ts` (gitignored, generated by build).

- **Build refactor.** `scripts/build-asm.js`: per-module memory flags
  (no more global `--initialMemory` with last-wins override),
  per-module `noSourceMap` option for the CT module.

- **ESLint.** `src/ts/ct-wasm.ts` added to ignores.

- **CI workflows.** 9 test files added to GitHub Actions workflows.
  `unit-fast.yml` +7, `unit-hashing.yml` +1, `unit-utils.yml` +1.
  Step names corrected. All 39 test files now covered.

### Test Suite

- 568 unit tests (Vitest), 186 e2e tests (Playwright × 3 browsers), 754 total.
- New test files: `pool.test.ts` (36), `sealstream.test.ts` (95),
  `sealstream_kat.test.ts` (18), `header.test.ts` (10), `errors.test.ts` (5),
  `pool.spec.ts` (4 × 3 browsers).
- Self-generated KAT vectors for SealStream v2: XChaCha20 (XC1, XC3, XCF1)
  and Serpent (SC1, SC3, SCF1) with framed variants. Each chunk independently
  verified against raw primitives.

